A Republican strategy to impede Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight against electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers this latter a myth and asserts that voter fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people who die from being struck by lightning.
en: In fact, Republican lawyers have found only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new regulations will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the US states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
In line with this, most American governments passed new laws from 2009 onwards making it more difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread following the November 2010 elections, which saw an increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, in 2011, 180 bills were introduced that restricted the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
en: Furthermore, those laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and remove the right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to require it.
The United States Supreme Court affirmed the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
Therefore, Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bill proposals in 34 states to require voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal form of identification, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any form of government-issued photo ID in their state.
English: On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identification document with those characteristics.
But often, obtaining the required identification document costs more than one hundred dollars.
Therefore, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and those with low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000 per year, 18% of citizens over 65 years old, and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years old do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who most vote for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
Furthermore, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who typically vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
en Arizona was the first state to implement such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are US citizens.
These measures clearly aim to limit Hispanic voting.
It appears that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported certain laws in 2011 that abolished same-day voter registration in eight states.
en: Furthermore, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create an assistance service for voters who wished to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
Additionally, Republican legislators passed laws in five other states that favored reducing the early voting period.
In the 2008 elections in Florida, for example, 33% of early voters were African American, while they only represented 13% of the state's electorate.
Spanish: En el caso de los hispanos, ocurría exactamente lo mismo.
These represent only 11% of the voters, which amounts to 24% of the citizens who vote early.
However, whites, who make up 76% of the electorate, only represent 46% of the citizens who voted early.
English: Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have vehemently opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
In this sense, Democratic governors have blocked several pieces of legislation.
The United States Department of Justice intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, to some extent, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these system-wide legislative changes will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new regulations will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Prostate Cancer Detection: Should I Get Tested or Not?
Indeed, the PSA test can sometimes produce inaccurate results, with false negatives or even false positives, leading to unnecessary medical interventions.
It is more than enough reason to make men, already reticent by nature, doubt whether they should or should not take the screening tests.
Should I take the test or not?
We have sought advice from two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, a high rate of infection was detected among the sample groups, making it difficult to interpret those data and make firm recommendations.
en: The European study showed some difference in mortality between patients who had undergone screening and those who had not.
The study, with a follow-up of 12 years, also showed that there is between 30 and 40% chance of developing metastasis if the screening test has not been done.
I therefore recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if your father has had prostate cancer.
African American men have a higher risk index.
The key is to make a good decision once cancer is detected.
There are aggressive cancers and other cancers that are indolent.
It is truly necessary to ensure that the patient understands the degree of risk of their cancer. All possible options should be offered and prostate cancers that do not pose a long-term threat to life should not necessarily be treated, in which case active surveillance of the disease should be chosen instead.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are not treated, since the cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a risk to their life.
We suggest active monitoring of the disease instead, and if it progresses, we offer treatment.
We are increasingly determining precise criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated.
I recommend that the test be done in any case.
But it is important to talk to your doctor to determine if you should get the test or not.
Movember has collaborated with the International Society of Urology to create a tool that allows for evaluating the pros and cons of the PSA test.
This document can be downloaded (currently only in English, but translations will be available soon) at the following address: http://ca.movember.com/en/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for preventing cancer.
Despite the progress of research, adopting healthy lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risks of getting the disease.
We estimate that if everyone ate well and moved enough, 30% of cancers could be prevented.
English: "If nobody smoked, that rate would at least increase by 50%,” emphasizes André Beaulieu, spokesperson for the Canadian Cancer Society.
We estimate that around 10% of cancers are hereditary.
Many others remain completely inexplicable.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, the fight against smoking remains a priority despite the decrease in the number of smokers.
Tobacco is linked to 85% of cases of lung cancer.
It also constitutes a risk factor for other types of cancers.
It hugely harms people's health.
en: Today, there are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec, said spokesperson André Beaulieu.
An encouraging statistic: 10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is halved.
The weight
Obesity and being overweight also increase the risk of disease, according to the SCC.
The risks of breast, colon and rectal, esophageal, pancreatic, and uterine cancer are increasing.
en: Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against breast cancer, they add.
Food
The organism recommends limiting the consumption of red meats as well.
In large amounts, they increase the risk of developing colorectal cancer.
Deli meats should also be avoided.
Meat preservation for smoking, drying, or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogenic substances.
They explain to us that it can damage the cells of the organism and lead to the development of cancer.
Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin complexes and cancer.
However, their research is not conclusive at the moment.
According to the SCC, studies about vitamin E are contradictory.
While one of them showed a decrease in prostate cancer risks, the other one showed an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer has also not been able to be determined clearly.
en: Furthermore, M. Beaulieu emphasizes the importance of discussing one's worries and family background with their doctor.
Taking the screening test does not cause cancer.
The Higgs Boson in Detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a great stir last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, indeed, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what's more, it is the particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model: our best or "least bad" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter, which has yet to be empirically observed.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Additionally, new data revealed this week at a major physics conference held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is needed to be completely sure.
en: We assume it is Higgs anyway, since the chances of being wrong seem slim. We will see what it is about.
Hey, in this great world, there is a widespread and unavoidable law that implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because you will end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of this kind in it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
en: On one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And then there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, meaning they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Lab's Particle Adventure website, which is quite extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't discuss here, and the "force particles" through which the fundamental forces of nature are propagated and with which the Higgs boson is somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic creatures we might think.
Indeed, if you are able to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "light particle" which acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that immediate environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing other than a photon; that is, one of the bosons "force carriers".
Stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, extremely high energies are required, a bit like a frozen pond in which only a large rock could slide across the surface.
Therefore, an immense particle accelerator like the one at CERN (the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km circumference ring!) is needed to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others don't: a piece of paper, for example, will never stay stuck to the door of a fridge by itself.
In the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what can all these researches contribute?, asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and SM predictions.
English: Meanwhile, many fervently wish that they will be found, as the smallest difference could open a door to a “new physics” that could patch up certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, such as not proposing any explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up around 80% of the matter in the Universe (another oops!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Consequences
The repercussions of such investigations on our daily lives are hard to predict, but we don't think we're wrong when we say there will be none.
To see: In the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work would cause.
They glimpsed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
Indeed, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was more of a "laboratory device".
Imagine...
And also, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light sensor in 1969 as part of his research in optics.
Despite it not being his original intention, this sensor now serves as the "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
en: Of course, that doesn't mean that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
en: Palliative Care. The Best Way to Die... | Le Devoir
In its Dying with Dignity Commission, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of end of life.
The debate must be resumed soon while a bill is being prepared.
Now, within that essential domain, there is still much to be done.
The Duty has tried to see it up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
Cancer of the prostate that was destroying him had given him a reprieve of two years.
"They had given me five years to live, but I've already been like this for seven," he recounts, withered away, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center in Beloeil, which he arrived at the day before.
en: "But it's always a shock, we can't be prepared for this," she continues.
The illness has wreaked havoc on him: a tremendous weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating by himself.
Sitting in front of a delicious lunch, he resignedly accepts help to eat.
Brave, she even smiles, talks to strangers who pay her attention, bring her medicine and offer her a bath.
The Courage of Ordinary Death.
en: "My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he confesses.
Later that day, the team found a remedy for the problem.
In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing up,” relates Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois Center.
To go back to one's childhood, for certain people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
en: "That depends on the person's ability to accept that regression," he notes.
Because, according to the opinion of most people working in palliative care, the great moments take place in the very heart of that regression.
All patients entering the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Center suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses surrounding them no longer provide "curative" care.
Mrs. A.'s greatest fear, at 89 years old, is to die "conscious and suffocating".
But the illness has made him discover his children.
en: "I have good children," he adds.
She says, "I have no more wishes in this life," before accepting the mask to help her breathe.
And wait, in the coming days, for one last visit from her son who lives in Italy.
Victor-Gadbois is offering, with a group of volunteers, body care and assistance with meals.
Palliative care is given when nothing else can be done.
To help make her passing more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all eventually die one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the center.
Whether it be on a physical, emotional, or spiritual level.
The dying are offered mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, depending on the demand.
Diabetics are no longer monitored for their blood sugar levels.
Death is a part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, who passed away during the night.
This morning, his son finished the beer at the feet of the deceased.
en: "We help both patients and their loved ones," reports Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
In Victor-Gadbois Center, days pass without ever being the same.
Beside a 94-year-old man savoring his last family gathering in the yard, comfortably nestled among his pillows while everyone toasts to his health, a 36-year-old tragically passes away surrounded by his parents, wife, and two children, having tried everything to survive.
For the past six months, there have been three to five beds occupied by people under 45 years old suffering from cancer, worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois center come from their home and 47% come from the hospital.
Access to Palliative Care Problem
Seventy-seven percent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to relieve suffering when a patient reaches the terminal stage of their life, whether at home, in the hospital, or in a care facility.
Several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Centre and the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, specialize almost exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
The lack of adequate healthcare in Quebec is precisely what has many specialized palliative care doctors fearing the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by palliative care luminaries such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the healthcare system in Quebec is not competent enough to ensure that everyone has access to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, I have seen a patient spend 14 days in the Emergency Room suffering from severe pain without anything being done to relieve her.
I fear that patients wish to die alone because they are not receiving the proper care.
At the same time, many oncologists remain dedicated to their patients until the very end, despite the worst prognoses.
Hélène Richard's hopes of survival were already at a minimum when she stopped an exhausting chemotherapy treatment.
When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop treatment, she told me she was very sorry that I wanted to give up fighting, he recounts.
en: However, she had told me there was nothing else to do!
There are no all-powerful caretakers.
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die are thankful to their caregivers for not having responded to their requests once their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of home palliative care in Grand Montreal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which serves to sleep the patient until the moment of their death, either sporadically or permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, untreated illness will have the possibility of having palliative sedation.
Patients who are not relieved say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want euthanasia", but "I want to be relieved".
This report was made possible through a journalism grant from the Canadian Institutes of Health Research.
Wide-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Road network officials, BTP entrepreneurs, political party fundraisers, and Italian mafia specialists tell, day after day, what they know about a formidable "system", which includes the construction industry, officials, politicians, unionists, and mafiosos.
en: An "industry" that became too expensive for Quebec taxpayers, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's curious how the system crumbles once we've caught the big guys," quips Jacques Duchesneau, a Quebec MP and former head of the Montreal Police.
He led the outburst of the scandal in 2011, which was made possible through an in-depth investigation into the misappropriations linked to highway contracts in Quebec, which the then Liberal Prime Minister Jean Charest had only consented to delay.
The "Duchesneau Report" established a direct link between industry, the clandestine financing of political parties, and corruption among officials.
From the start of the investigation in 2010, only the Ministry of Transportation would have saved one billion dollars in contracts, containing some of its instincts to take a proportional share.
The Charbonneau Commission "has already brought down two mayors," it adds, while hoping to be able to "demonstrate the stratagems existing behind the individuals".
An anti-corruption permanent unit, established in 2011.
The Permanent Anticorruption Unit, established in 2011, is also applied with its team of government auditors, investigators, and analysts.
This unit works in addition to the police of "Squad Marteau", which, since 2009, have made the "Sewer Cartel" of Montreal moderate when it comes to inflating contracts.
Over the past few weeks, the unit has been carrying out a series of investigations into fraud and corruption allegations against municipal officials such as Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, the mayor of a town on the outskirts.
Next on the list is Gilles Vaillancourt, who recently resigned from his position as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third largest city.
It is suspected that multiple bribes have been pocketed in exchange for public contracts.
Engineers of Montreal's road network and Italian-origin businessmen, such as Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito, have been formally charged.
This last one has caused shock when explaining to the commission the mechanics of the "system" for obtaining public contracts.
He himself paid 3% of the value of the contracts obtained in Montreal for three years to an intermediary linked to the mafia who transferred the money to Union Montréal, the party of Mayor Gérald Tremblay.
Mr. Zambito distributed money left and right during the 2000s, granting more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to provincial parties, especially to the ruling Liberals.
He also admitted to organizing an illegal fundraising campaign for former Liberal Deputy Prime Minister, Nathalie Normandeau.
The inflation of the cost of sewer contracts
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption operated effectively.
Gilles Surprenant, a former public works engineer, explained it perfectly to the commission: over a ten-year period he received gifts, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey games and bribes from construction sector companies totaling $736,000, all in exchange for contracts for sewerage work whose costs he inflated.
Other road network officials have admitted that they received money to inflate invoices by between 30% and 40% for false extras.
Additionally, an organizer of the Mayor Martin Dumont's party accused M. Tremblay of deliberately turning a blind eye to a parallel budget and filling his coffers with dirty money.
Following these revelations, M. Tremblay resigned at the beginning of November, leading Montreal into a huge crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first elected politicians in Montreal to sound the alarm.
As mayor of the Rivière-des-Prairies district in the east of the island, she has opposed since 2010 the sale of a municipal land acquired for 5 million dollars and resold for 1.6 million to developers in the midst of a real estate boom.
Seventy percent of the money for election campaigns was dirty money.
From the research that will eventually be carried out, she ensures that she will "pull a thread to understand the functioning of the system, infiltrated by ants, to stop the gangrene and fish out the culprits".
He adds that the process is "painful, but positive".
We are cleaning up the wounds but there is a need for a clean investigative unit in Montreal and to be very vigilant so that dubious practices do not repeat.
How to do the cleaning.
Spanish: Regularmente.
Jacques Duchesneau stated that "officials have stolen hundreds of millions of dollars", but he is most concerned about the role of the "elected politicians aware of the scheme".
English: Estimating at 70% the proportion of dirty money that was used to finance electoral campaigns in Quebec, he quips: "I have been told that this is only a pale reflection of reality."
The Quebec government proposes to limit political party donations to $100, but that won't change the donation, according to him, "as long as electoral spending is not strictly limited, there will be dirty money in politics".
Recommend a full review of the public contract awarding and party funding system: "We cannot fall any lower; going to the bottom of things, with courage, will allow us to rebuild the house on stronger foundations, with more controls and laws."
If this story tarnishes the international image of Quebec and Montreal, M. Duchesneau invites those who laugh to look in the mirror.
en: "PSG is not FC Barcelona!"
This season has taken on a new identity with PSG.
How would you explain that progress?
It could be explained by individual awareness, but also by the new dimension of PSG.
Great players have arrived.
I move forward day by day by your side.
The technical staff has also contributed a lot to me.
Those elements push me to raise the level of my game every day.
In a game, that's easier.
Everything moves very fast in football.
But I don't get worked up.
Since my start at INF Clairefontaine's training center to my time at Saint-Etienne, I have made giant strides.
You will benefit from the competition recruited by Carlo Ancelotti.
The recruits of this summer are used to playing high-level games.
They know that every training is crucial.
That makes a player like me want to fight and give it my all.
Furthermore, Carlo Ancelotti has been very helpful in terms of my positioning.
He is backed up by attachments like Claude Makelele, who played in the same position as me.
Is Ancelotti the man that the team needed?
en: Of course.
All coaches respect Ancelotti.
Today, there is no one like him in League 1 and he is among the best European coaches.
He has a great deal of experience and has won numerous titles with the top clubs.
He has worked with great players.
I think she will take other titles in Paris.
In January I had a very comforting conversation with him.
I had just come out of a series of injuries.
The trust he has in me explains my good performance as well.
What do you think about PSG in the first half of the season?
In Ligue 1, Lyon has taken away our top spot.
But we remain in ambush.
One of our biggest goals is the Champions League: we have qualified for the round of 16 in style.
What is the goal of the club in this competition?
Let's try to go as far as we can.
From now on, anything can happen.
But we have a lot to say against many and very good European teams.
We want, to start off, to finish first in our league against Porto in order to receive the return of the eighth-finals.
Can PSG become a great European club in the short term?
He already has the budget...
To become a great European club, Paris must win titles and be there for the long haul.
Today, that is not the case.
Economically, PSG is committed to its means to make this project a reality.
Would not winning the cup in League 1, as in the last season, be a huge failure?
en: Of course, it would be a great disappointment.
This year we are going to invest all our efforts in taking that championship title.
We didn't get very far in the last season.
In May we were disappointed, as we had the optimal conditions to finish first.
We had a strong season.
We ended with 79 points.
Normally, with 79 points we should have been champions...
But another team, Montpellier, had a much better season.
This year I think it will be the good one.
Even if big teams like Marseille, Lyon and Bordeaux fight for the title, I believe we have the weapons to take it.
Do you think the media expects more from PSG?
It is normal for them to expect a lot from us if we consider what has been invested in the players we have.
We have fully accepted it.
After we won 4-0 at home against Troyes, it is a bit frustrating that there are still things to be criticized.
We wonder what else people are expecting.
We will never win 4-0 every weekend.
We are not FC Barcelona!
We are trying to get a game project off the ground.
Building a team takes time.
In the Champions League we have shown that we can respond and be present.
Look at Manchester City, who after two seasons have failed to qualify for the knockout stages, and they have invested a lot too!
Given the amounts invested, we would expect you to have a 15 point lead at the end of the day.
That would be neglecting our opponents and the French championship.
Lyon and Marseille, who were not doing well last season, have been "boosted" by this new PSG.
That shows that League 1 is thrilling.
I hope that by May we can say with a smile that, despite all the difficulties, we have ended up taking the trophy.
The PSG seems totally dependent on the successes of Zlatan Ibrahimovic.
Let's just say we have a "Zlatandependency".
That means Ibrahimovic is very capable and he scores a lot of goals.
He has come to show that he is the star of League 1.
He has proven in every team he has been on that he is a great player, a world-class star.
We respect the man and the player in the group.
He also respects the men around him.
What he has done is truly exceptional.
That pushes others to raise their game.
English: Thiago Silva, one of the best defenders in the world, also allows us all to progress.
How have you experienced the Euro 2012 with the French team?
It has been a disappointment.
I was very excited to participate in this Euro Cup.
Unfortunately, my injury prevented me from accumulating playing time.
We saw things there and left feeling strengthened.
Today I managed to play good games on the team.
en: It's what I've been expecting since my baptism with the "bleus".
We learned the lesson from what happened in Ukraine and that is why we have exemplary behavior today.
What is your vision of Didier Deschamps' first month in charge of the "bleus"?
He is getting results.
They are well placed in the World Cup qualifying group.
The coach is rigorous, close to the players and inspires to win.
As was the case with Laurent Blanc.
But I don't want to make comparisons.
en: Blanc achieved his goal of qualifying us for the Euro Cup.
I hope Didier Deschamps takes the team to Brazil.
Did the 1-1 draw on October 16 in Spain serve to lay the foundations?
That game gave us confidence.
Everyone fought for everyone.
Before that shock in Spain, I had never experienced a similar game throughout my career.
With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
en: The opposite of current monetary exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between parties.
Additionally, as is often the case with technology, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
en: In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a convertible virtual currency to dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol similar to BitTorrent, which allows for peer-to-peer file sharing.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
Approximately one thousand websites accept Bitcoin as donations or as a form of payment.
After reaching a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, the Bitcoin rate dropped to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (rates are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
It's nothing impressive if we compare it to global changes in real currency or financial products.
en However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in it in an October report on virtual currencies.
In it, Bitcoin was described as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
English: Bitcoin differs from other virtual currency systems such as "credits", used to progress in a video game and which can be earned by playing or bought (and sometimes even exchanged).
Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange, a central authority controls and handles the changes.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously bookkeepers, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
en: How does that network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses.
English: A user can choose a different address for each payment, ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that Bitcoin changes are recorded in the public ledger, which is broadcast across the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that ledger.
This passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge issued to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file slicing phase, that is, transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
en: Computers "grab" the new transaction and add a number before "breaking up" the set.
The goal is to find the number that provides a particular footprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once the number is found, the other nodes can easily verify that it is the correct one.
The transaction is then indelibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
Yes, if a user were to attempt to commit fraud by paying twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would become orphaned, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge will get 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, that reward will be divided regularly, with probability before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the hundred-millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in every increase in computing power.
The ups and downs of life on the network are already here.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins held in deposit have been stolen.
Pierre Noizat, who recently launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network, assures that "the bug used does not affect the same protocol".
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same drawback.
Heavyweight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that around 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, the "Giant Sales" were launched.
English:  "$30,000 was exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of an educational book on that currency, is quite confident in the potential of this technology as well as the transaction network.
Paytunia is their system, which is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, making them cheaper.
The carrier also manages their identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up in stores, with no need to install new terminals or software.
All you need to provide is an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement towards replacing hierarchical systems with more horizontal systems.
It will take time for Bitcoin to become established, but there could be a shift in 2013, predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also foresees revaluating the various risks, currently considered high, should this currency be successful.
We have left Afghanistan.
And then?
The French troops have withdrawn from their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans must withdraw by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take back possession of its territory and for Afghans to choose their own future, without expecting anything from us.
We have punished Afghan peasants in particular, whom we have deemed to be terrorists.
And to ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, plus the wounded and the maimed.
The Taliban have foreign extremists and former leaders who are refugees in Pakistan, but often also local villagers who reject the presence of foreign troops, as in the times of the Soviets.
They want to defend their traditions, old and archaic, even if jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks or Tajiks join their causes.
They will no longer be tolerated, or even sometimes aided by local insurgents, when the Westerners become more discreet.
I observed the departure of the French troops from the Nijrab base, which was made by order, from the top of the almond-planted hills thanks to French credits.
The convoy of trucks and tanks returned to Kabul unharmed, watched over by helicopters.
There will be no influx of Taliban in Kabul from the end of 2014.
The circumstances have changed since its unstoppable advance between 1994 and 1996.
Kabul was then empty and the country engulfed in fire and blood due to the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country had been seen as a kind of liberation, a return to safety.
Afghans have paid the price for the ignorance of their rural population overwhelmed by Al-Qaeda, but their situation is not better today.
The elderly mujahideen, the current government, and the current Taliban all share a desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
In 2001, the main figures of the anti-Soviet war returned to power.
They have become speculators, taking over government land to resell as plots for the refugees who have returned from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge US subcontracting contracts.
They are discredited; most of them have not fought.
People, according to what I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government not composed of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have taken advantage of American generosity: capital flight is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They have experienced the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan and have appreciated its advantages.
With around 65% of its population under 25 years old, Kabul currently has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
In cities, state schools are filled with both girls and boys.
We must give work to those young people who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or the corruption of certain leaders.
Everyone, including the armed opposition, is eager for mobile phones. Turkish television and its soap operas portraying a modern world have many admirers across the country.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who wish to lead the country be considered legitimate?
The former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are now concerned with reconstituting the provincial militias, which will flee from central power.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from some degree of decentralization, similar to Western nations. However, the United States has sought to transform it into a centralized state, with a strong presidential power, eliminating the post of Prime Minister that had existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign control, particularly in relation to the upcoming elections in April 2014.
Despite this, their country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and even earlier.
No industry has resumed its services, no reservoir has been repaired and no important irrigation systems have been fixed.
Everything is imported and nothing is produced except for fruits and vegetables.
Private initiative should take priority.
In a country ruined after 30 years of war, government control would have been necessary.
Rumors spread that Afghanistan had immense mineral wealth.
That only increased the feeling that Westerners were there to take over.
Without energy to extract the iron or copper minerals from the land and without means of transportation to export them through the mountains, there is no mining.
Chinese miners have almost completely abandoned the copper mines of Mes Aynak, allowing international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the immense Buddhist site and remain there as the most important employers in the province.
It will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, a country on which imports and exports depend heavily, to restore normal relations.
The French troops departed on November 20th.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aid: girls' schools, boys' schools, a French department at the university, the French Institute, cooperation in military, legal, health and agricultural fields, and support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to try to reconcile aid and offensive actions, a "civil-military action" service of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, brought and had brought through a small French NGO numerous collective interest works and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
Those jobs, eager to obtain local labor, have been able to help contain the insurrection: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, sun protection and increased cultivation areas.
What will we leave behind as a reminder after two million euros of military spending?
A modest budget will contribute to improving the local living conditions, which are often very harsh in these valleys located at more than 2,000 meters above sea level.
The Embassy received dozens of written requests with small agricultural proposals made by local communities in the province of Kapisa.
To free themselves from the insurrection carried out by foreign groups, something the farmers have told me they desire, would require a small, well-controlled, and direct civil aid.
An Constitution by Forceps in Egypt
en: It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration granting him provisional full powers, he decided to go all in.
en: It took everyone by surprise on Wednesday when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Last week, the head of state had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
It has been almost two years since Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been modified several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal entanglements.
This new initiative has only served to widen the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delusion" and continues to "betray his word" and "tread on the law".
Supporters of the measure claim that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and accelerate the transition process.
In the next 15 days a referendum should be organized.
A very short period of time forced the Brothers to abandon their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi appears confident that Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly magazine Time.
es:  Dado que este recurso fue votado con mucha rapidez, contiene un ultimátum para el pueblo egipcio: "o votan mi texto o mantengo los poderes plenos", poderes que supuestamente terminarán con la adopción de la Constitución.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
In the middle of November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they thought they could not make their views heard.
Human rights advocates, religious minorities, and civil society representatives did the same.
In order to reach the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted on have been unanimously.
Commentators find it amusing, on the other hand, that one of the few disagreements of the day was expressed almost at prayer time, so much so that several members of the committee even thought that the clock of the Constituent was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all eyes, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, were hoping that "principles" could be replaced by "rules", which would have allowed for a stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals accuse it of hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a publicity stunt.
They claim that the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They are referring, in particular, to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, particularly for anyone who has to confirm their compliance with Sharia laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is concerning because "the people called upon to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy.
The fears of the liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of the university would be considerably less moderate than the current one.
en: There is currently no specific religious implication.
With this Constitution, we are within the framework of civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on that text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
We are specifically referring to the term iqh (Islamic jurisprudence).
The question that might be asked in the future would be to what extent are civil judges competent to rule on all of this?
Beyond its religious character, the text voted on yesterday has received many criticisms referring to the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will argue that they are few in comparison to those who were during the previous regime.
Another contentious issue: the powers granted to the military.
According to the military's wishes, the review of the Defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defense Council.
No processing of civilians in military courts will be prohibited either, as requested by human rights defense associations.
These also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider to be oppressive.
Blasphemy remains a crime and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly for the press.
Furthermore, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
She said the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture according to Article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to appear on television last night, demonstrations are expected for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
Ukrainian tourists in Israel can expect the holy land, the navel of the world, and a sea of salt.
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Biblical truths with modern comforts and pristine nature.
en: "AIF" identified the five most important reasons to visit Israel.
Respect in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal pool" will receive divine grace.
In Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm, and the nets full of fish.
In this same place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places can be found in Jerusalem.
English: Believers here walk the Stations of the Cross or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
Begin at Antonio Fortress, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continue through the streets of the Old City, go to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, to the Stone of Anointing and to the place of Jesus' burial.
Here also lies the symbolic Christian Navel of the world, symbolizing the salvation of humanity.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the spot where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus was made.
In Jerusalem is also located the most sacred place for Jews, the Western Wall; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their wishes, which will then come true.
Take a vertical journey
The ruins of Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge against enemies, which Herod the Great ordered to be built in the year 25 BC for his family.
They are located on mountain cliffs at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who practice climbing can reach there by their own means.
Others can reach this historic summit by funicular.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
en: Bus services are available from the foot of the hill up to there.
The total length of the ski trails is 45 km.
According to an old legend, pagan gods were supposedly living on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are around 300 museums.
You can't visit them all in one trip.
But it's worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting ones.
The Israel Museum is among them, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It houses the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, and around 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Art Museum in Tel Aviv.
In her painting exhibition she has canvases from Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, and Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha Museum-Bath, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers from that era.
It is worth visiting the exclusive private museum Ralli in Cesarea, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops there.
Entry is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, displays one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in complete darkness.
The stars shine.
They sound the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea, and the Dead Sea.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that people swim in the Red Sea even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and people swim there all year round.
en: By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 meters below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustain even those who don't know how to swim.
The landscapes of the surroundings are truly beautiful.
People come here to take courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing muds and to strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Uncovering the mysteries of antiquity
The old part of Tel Aviv, the Jaffa Citadel, preserves it on the Mediterranean coast.
She was passed by the famous maritime route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here where Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets that bear the names of the Zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa, newlyweds couples can be found coming from all over Israel, and even from other countries, to have their photos taken.
In Cesarea, the city of King Herod, you can take a walk around the Roman theatre and explore the Crusader fortress.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of the Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theater, carefully restored, is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, remember!
If you travel to Israel, don't worry if your English is not very good: around 30% of the population speaks Russian in this country.
It is not advisable to take money for this trip in Euros, but in Dollars, which can easily be exchanged for Shekels (currently 1-3$,8 Shekels).
Urban transportation is mainly composed of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa there is the country's only metro line, consisting of six stations and connecting the Lower City with the Upper City.
It's actually from an underground funicular.
It costs 6 shekels to travel on any type of public transport, and for this price you can transfer and travel for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Saturdays are celebrated as the Sabbath.
From Friday night until Saturday sunset, markets and stores close and public transportation stops working.
But Sunday morning marks the start of a new work week.
In many cafes, restaurants, and hotels, only Kosher food is served, which excludes pork, shellfish, fish without scales, and dishes combining milk and meat.
There is a wide selection of beef and lamb dishes, soups and desserts made with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a variety of sauces, falafel, which are ground chickpea balls, fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities, no stray dogs can be seen.
In contrast, there are many well-fed cats that "roam at their own leisure" in an imposing manner.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Ronroneadores love crowded places and don't turn down treats.
The rental of a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
en: In addition to the insurance, which is $15 per day.
The rental of a bicycle will cost you 15 shekels per day.
The admission to museums costs an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in Numbers
In 2012, over three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to tour the country and rest were citizens of the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom, and Ukraine.
Ukrainian tourists visited The Promised Land from January to October 2012, amounting to 118,800, which is 51% higher than the same index in 2010 before the visa regime was cancelled on February 9th, 2011.
en: The great and powerful will take you to Moscow: immigrants save for the language.
While legislators and human rights advocates debate the consequences of the mandatory testing law, scammers selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families who have been stuck at home.
As of December 1st, a law will come into effect, according to which every working immigrant must take an exam to verify their knowledge of the Russian language.
English: This rule is currently applicable only to those intending to work in the service provision, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade sectors.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
Additionally, it will not be enough to take the language exam, but also the Russian history exam and the fundamentals of legislation exam.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed in order to receive and renew a work permit.
Except for citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
en: Those who obtained their education certificates and diplomas prior to the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Utility, Fatalism, and Defense of Rights
The network of testing centers will be sponsored by the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University, and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take tests in all cities, currently over 160 such centers are open in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the test was supported by the State Duma deputies and the Federal Immigration Service.
But defenders of rights, long before the law came into effect, often managed to ask the press: What will this really bring?
What changes will the requirement of language knowledge bring for both Russians and immigrants themselves?
First of all, Immigration Service representatives answer, this will help reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
Many people are talking today about the defense of the rights of migrant workers, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Migration Service of Russia in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will be able to resolve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
Immigrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language or pass the medical exam have the problems.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev claims, the future immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, will put him on a "paid trip" to a creepy and cramped shack, where he and dozens of others like him will be consumed for months without food or documents, working from 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received a multitude of complaints from our immigrants.
In their home country they are promised one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, their passports are taken away from them, and they are not paid the promised wages, confirms Tolib Sharipov, Head of the Labor Immigration Department of the Immigration Service of Tajikistan.
en: Don't be angry, boss!
However, in the meantime, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that not only do they not know the language of the country they are trying to go to, but also that they have difficulty writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their own misfortune: there are few Turkmen, Uzbek, and Tajik people who can afford to receive a normal primary education.
This is because their families don't even have anything to give the children to eat, let alone clothe them, put shoes on them, and buy them what they need for school.
Upon reaching adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if one does not know the language, for them to recognize it.
One feels humiliated and inferior.
However, when it comes to language law, defenders of rights point to an important point.
Exams will only be held for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be neither an exam nor, consequently, any official job.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
Welcome or no entry for strangers
Many visitors claim that getting official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
en: Furthermore, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a fake registration can be done quickly and for only fifteen hundred rubles.
Russian police officers know that we usually carry fake documents, are unregistered, and cases of extortion appear.
Umed Hushkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, commented to journalists that they are asked for one hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea.
Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting.
On the first day of the language law coming into effect, it was made clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be falsified.
Several "fake" language proficiency certificates have already been seized by Immigration and Customs Enforcement officials.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to make it easier to pass the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, bringing together government officials and rights defenders.
So far, authorities can promise immigrant workers who have not been able to pass the test the first time more time to study the basic language course.
Additionally, jobs that do not require active communication with people will be offered to immigrants who do not speak Russian.
The Ministry of the Interior does not take drastic measures against the illegal trade of weapons.
The percentage of crimes committed with registered weapons is quite low.
The Ministry of the Interior proposes to enforce the law more strictly with regard to civilian gun owners.
The government's response to the recent incidents is: Crackdown on wedding celebrations which luckily had no casualties, and the massacre initiated by Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinogradov, in which seven people lost their lives.
The police want to ban the use and possession of firearms in public places and raise the minimum age for obtaining a license to carry firearms, from 18 to 21 years old.
This idea was supported by the head of the State Duma's security and anti-corruption committee, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that reforms to the law on gun possession will be brought to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy with the fact that Russian authorities are trying to counter this problem by applying a "hard-line policy".
An open letter has appeared online, whose authors, representatives of various shooting organizations, demand that such "senseless rigor" measures be abandoned.
The percentage of acts of vandalism involving firearms is minimal, Vasiliy Lésnikov, a criminal lawyer, told the BBC Russia news service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, during the six months of 2012, 142 crimes involving the use of registered firearms in the Interior were committed, compared to the total of 1168 crimes registered for this same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that stricter legislation in the civilian firearms sector will not be an obstacle for the criminal to turn to the black market.
Now, according to his words, in Moscow any weapon can be found at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior states that the situation of the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officials
The black market for weapons is supplied through various channels.
The main channels are years, says retired Colonel Victor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and in the High Command.
en: Screenshot of the website accepting orders for weapons
The first, "vestige of the army or military", refers to the weapons that were stolen during military actions in the Caucasus.
en: Baranets says that the weapons were stolen by the Russian officers and by the Caucasians themselves.
Black market firearms, stolen by criminals and law enforcement personnel.
Baranets explains that this includes weapons stolen from police warehouses and those directly stolen by law enforcement officers.
Illegal weapons are being sold from military arsenals.
In many military arsenals there were often explosions.
"There are proven accounts that some fires were deliberately set to cover up a shortage," comments a former soldier.
According to Baranets, arms manufacturers also do their part.
Now private arms factories have proliferated which are not competitive in the international market and distribute weapons under the table to the black market, including Moscow's, says the expert.
One more source of the black market is smuggling.
A large number of guns and machine guns come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
They have their own production, sometimes artisanal, and a mafia has formed that has organized the flow of weapons," explains the ex-military.
en: Where do the weapons come from?
Experts have calculated the approximate share of each of these sources of illegal weapons supply to the black market.
An report on this topic was prepared in 2011 by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Management Planning.
English: Experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminological bibliography and public access data from portals whose theme revolves around weapons.
Most illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from military and security forces.
Half of the black market weapons have arrived there "due to officials whose job is related to weapons," the report says.
According to researchers, 17% of weapons come from places where there are armed conflicts, 14% of cases are stolen during the production of weapons, and 5% corresponds to "illegal archaeology".
The attendant of one of the gun stores, who asked that his last name not be mentioned, says that the guns found by illegal excavators are not bought by anyone for a long time because they are too old.
He says that more often, suppliers go to military warehouses when they need a shipment.
Through a warrant officer, the supplier purchases one unit, for example a TT pistol.
They remove her from the registry and pass her over the fence.
This person takes the weapon to the city and sells it for 900 euros per unit with two magazines, they tell us.
But of course, the police are aware of all matters, so periodically, when the crime discovery plan needs to be fulfilled, they make test purchases from illegal arms dealers,” adds the clerk.
Like in a luxury boutique
The seller and buyer usually meet through acquaintances.
I visited websites and blogs until a guy suggested that I go to the "Begovaya" platform, where a man would take me to a "corner" where we could negotiate.
I only found out the price of the weapon there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranets
The shop attendant says, "I need a friend with connections to get a gun. I have a friend like that, but I don't trust him much."
In the markets there are sellers, but there one also has to arrive, let's say "on behalf of Mr. Ivanovih, who asked to be told that his daughter had lost a tooth".
Even I can get a pair of steel gloves through a trusted person.
He also supplies them to me alone because he knows I won't rat him out.
Newcomers seek weapons in various ways.
Former military officer Viktor Baranets tested himself in the role of illegal arms buyer in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
en: The schemes, according to their words, have not changed.
