Employees of fast food restaurants and supermarkets in the US are going on strike.
Approximately one quarter of American teenagers find their first jobs as cashiers at McDonald's.
In the United States, a wave of protests has been sparked in recent days against the low wages paid to workers at Walmart corporation supermarkets and popular fast food chains such as McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's, and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one is willing to assert yet whether this wave will reach the nine points or if it will lose strength and subside in its early stages.
The protest actions have the support of the unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to the modest wage increases received by Walmart and fast food workers, the goal of the protest organizers is to create worker unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has practically not been occupied by the labor movement.
Is forty-six cents per year?
en: Last week's shopping frenzy began on Thanksgiving Day, also known as "Black Friday". On that day, millions of Americans embarked on a shopping spree that sometimes ended in clashes.
On that day, some workers of the Walmart corporation, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left their jobs and formed picket lines in protest alongside unions and left-wing activists at the corporation's stores, whose products are aimed at people with modest and moderate incomes.
en: Walmart sells everything from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries, to vacuums, eggs and milk.
The products in your stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those of the larger supermarkets.
This is why many of the underpaid workers at Walmart only shop at work.
Availability and selection of products have made Walmart one of the largest corporations in America.
According to two critics, Walmart can afford to sell products at very low prices, partly because it pays its workers low wages.
These workers also complain about the poor working conditions, such as the lack of forklifts or hand scanners.
On "Black Friday," the participants of the protest demanded a raise in wages and complained that the cost of the health insurance provided by the corporation had gone from $30 to $100 per month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who makes $9.50 an hour, this expenditure is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California at Berkeley argue that if Walmart raises the average wage to $12 per hour, it will cost the corporation $3.2 billion.
This is approximately 1.1% more than what is spent on salaries now.
If Walmart puts the wage increase on the shoulders of consumers, each visit to the store will cost them just 46 cents more.
In one year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they are spending now.
Supporters of Walmart are pleased to note that the protest only took place in nine states and caused no loss to the corporation.
en: Walmart's "Black Friday" extended in their stores from 8 PM on Thursday to midnight the next day, and during that time, Walmart sold around 5000 items per second.
In total, their cash registers processed almost 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
Dan Fogelman, the company representative, stated in an interview with the left-wing website Huffington Post that less than five Walmart employees had left their jobs and that the protest had been nothing more than "another PR stunt" organized by the workers' union.
Free box!
Protests continued this week in New York, targeting not the big box stores Walmart (which has no love in this progressive city, and thus far there are none), but rather McDonald's and other cheap restaurants.
en: McDonald's claims to sell billions of servings, yet they won't even give you sick leave and won't pay you for your honest work!
en: Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
Currently, according to both federal and New York state law, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food restaurants are gradually increasing wages, but only slightly, and on average, ordinary workers in New York make $8.90 per hour.
en: No one earns less than them in this city.
How is it possible to survive in New York with that money, it's incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of American teenagers passed through McDonald's and worked there, behind the counters, part-time after school, even though they still lived with their parents.
Few saw this as the main source of income or planned to stay there for long.
Now, I constantly stumble upon interviews with McDonald's workers who complain that they have to live off of this salary, and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, in a forum of the Wall Street Journal magazine there is a comment whose author points out that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30am on Thursday at the McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that fast food cashiers and cooks be paid at least $15 an hour, doubling their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that unions for workers be created in the fast food sector.
The US law prohibits the administration from denying this right and punishing union movement activists with tricks and dismissals.
English: On the other hand, the administration rarely makes life easier for them.
But, for objective reasons, it is easy for unions to cover the fast food sector.
Excessive staff turnover is one of the main issues.
Discordant
Loud protests took place that same day at other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The climax of the action took place halfway through the rally at the McDonald's near Times Square, which was attended by several local Democratic politicians, in particular City Council Member Jumaane Williams, who said: "McDonald's says it's selling billions of portions, and then it doesn't even give you a hospital or pay you for your honest work."
en: The protesters received support from other prominent New York Democrats, such as mayoral candidate Bill de Blasio, who said, "We must support fast-food workers in their fight for fair wages and the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves."
As described by the New York Times, this has been the largest demonstration of its kind in American fast food history.
But only a few hundred people participated in it, not even all of them were employees of the fast food service, which employs tens of thousands of people in New York.
It is still unclear if this will spark a massive movement.
For now, fooling the brain is not so easy.
Augmented reality, so popular among tech enthusiasts, has recently become commonplace primarily through the use of special glasses.
At the start of summer, at its annual conference Google demonstrated a moving model and later, in November, it was revealed that Microsoft had also filed a patent application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Sharam Izadi, it was revealed that for the scientists at the company, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted to the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
en: Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also strive to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
For now, humanity as a whole has been stuck in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with their finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the major changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, since everyone is interested in gesture control.
en: What else does the future hold for us?
Despite Kinect bringing interaction to a physical level, much of it still takes place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), but the output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design ones.
We must free the world of computing from ours, the physical one, and make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around them.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more convenient way.
First of all, to hell with those silly virtual reality headsets!
en: What do you think about voice control?
Is a popular detail, but don't you think it's overrated?
en: Of course it cannot be considered a panacea, the issue of privacy remains unresolved, as we do not always want others to know our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought of gestures, but not of loose movements, but rather shorter ones.
Additionally, the gestures were not captured by the device's camera, but by a wristband that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
en: It is currently very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
en - How is that?
English: For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can of soda?
You will speak and show at the same time.
en - I usually just speak.
Oh, that's going to be really hard to recognize.
Is it that you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do right now?
Not necessarily, but it is a mutual approach.
I believe that in the near future we will have to primarily work on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine a person's reactions.
These could be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good depth resolution, which is very important.
en: If we are talking about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with 3D recognition.
en: Of course, it would be great to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the issue is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
English: So, we have to remember not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also in Z.
en: Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are truly scarce, especially for gestures.
en: Steven Bathiche, from our lab in Redmond, created an adjustable processing delay contact sensor ranging from 1 to 100 ms and it is worth noting that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the latter value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects human-machine interaction.
I would find it very useful for my work to have an equivalent of such a device that does not require contact in order to increase the frames per second.
Is it not necessary to increase the number of cameras?
English: The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually the infrared ray emitter and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually just a simple visible spectrum sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or, conversely, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be good to create a flexible analog of Kinect, play with the curvature of camera placement and see how this would help to determine three-dimensional position.
En: From what I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Doesn't it seem that, from the point of view of daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
en: Of course, holding up a smartphone all the time is not very comfortable, but I think the best option would be a transmutable augmented reality where, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to a smartphone.
Glasses are very personal devices, that is their strength (private things only you can see them), but also their weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
Let's imagine for a moment that manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any ordinary mortal.
There is one problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile response!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers is your group preparing for this challenge?
I often say in my lectures that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
Register the perfect touch!
But there are also technologies that are truly aimed at providing tangibility to these "images in the air". For example, the interference of several ultrasound beams directed to a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what one feels if someone were blowing on the fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wristbands that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this is also a promising direction.
Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think he feels what he should feel when he sees something?
That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another challenge we will have to grapple with for a long time: how to make a person physically located in a very confined space feel like they are in an open, almost limitless space. We are also working on the idea of treadmill-like platforms, as well as giant balloons.
Tricking the brain is not so easy right now, it will take many years of work.
That is what makes working with virtual reality attractive to researchers, as many things are found in a state of total conception.
Personal subjective preference instead of culture - Rosbalt.ru
en: "Rosbalt" continues the "St. Petersburg Vanguard" project, dedicated to citizens who are at the forefront of art and culture.
This list of the best features brilliant figures from the art and scene of St. Petersburg, whose achievements reach beyond the city: often they find recognition in Europe without Russia even knowing them.
The new hero of "Rosbalt" is the flamboyant artist Kirill Miller.
Everyone in the city knows Kirill Miller, a bearded man dressed head to toe in red, who can be found near the Russian Museum, near the Summer Garden or at fashion and opening events.
Kirill Miller's paintings always draw crowds wherever they are exhibited.
Kirill Miller is one of those purely sociophilosophical storytellers from Saint Petersburg, creating new mythologies.
Kirill Miller is a brilliant representative of the St. Petersburg avant-garde of the late 80s - early 90s.
He is also an urban man, whose presence on the streets of the city brings smiles to the inhabitants and lifts everyone's mood.
Recently, he took up an organ grinder and became the organ grinder of St. Petersburg, as he has matured to take on such a difficult role, owing to his bohemian existence, his philosophy, and his image.
En: Kirill, why are you going around the city dressed in red and not in yellow or turquoise, for example?
I chose the color red because I am a fashion designer and I focus on appearance and image.
In this world, red is a compromise between the artist, image makers, and society.
Although in society, anything that isn't a bit grey can provoke aggression and stir up bad properties.
But my provocations are meant to start a conversation.
All the story of my provocative actions is an invitation to debate.
en: When did you realize you had to be an artist?
In an exhibition at the Nevsky Culture Palace, where my works were displayed.
I realized that this was my path.
Then the wave of old, unofficial artists had ended, and the new, free ones like me were still misunderstood.
I became friends with artists of the new wave, those who followed those exhibited in Gaza and Nevskiy, which led to "Pushkinskaya-10", and the new wave was over.
I immersed myself in the theater for the clothes, the music of all genres, but not for the lyrics.
All of this came together at your Art Clinic... - It was important for me to find myself in the cultural center of St. Petersburg, where the best creative minds were supposed to come together.
In 1995, I occupied a territory in Pushkinskaya-10 and there, before any reforms, existed an artistic music club, a bohemian club, the house of bohemia of Saint Petersburg.
Many were born there: Noms, Tequila Jazz, I remember the way Schnur brought the project to "La oreja de Van Gogh".
Schnur and his friends were singing light songs under the phonogram, wearing tight pants, among them was the currently fashionable composer Igor Vdovin.
When the group started playing live, it became "Leningrad".
Trachtenberg hosted many shows before the times of Hali-galivskih.
We gave it to Trachtenberg and it was the start of his great career; he received his basic education and training from us.
Gallery "D 137" and "Club Griboyedov" are the remnants of the Art Clinic.
Our employees and regular customers were going there.
I am a hero of the past century, when culture meant something.
In 2000, the survey was conducted in the press, the prize was "The People of Our City".
I was chosen for the "Artist of the Year" nomination, and that marked the culmination of my career.
In these new times, it is not comfortable to work; I am a man who likes the truth, honesty, and the culture of the last century.
In our times it is easy to become popular, but culture and popularity go separate ways. One can be popular but very uncultured.
There is something recognizable in your work.
Many of my paintings are hits, in them the current and the occurrence are clearly expressed.
I am going to do a scheduled presentation, "The Russian Museum of Clowns".
Clowns are a timeless category.
I used to be sociable, but now being that way is painful and terrifying.
But in clowns everything is smeared and tragedy is eliminated.
I love the grotesque, I have grotesque ideas.
For example, the salvation of the world through a totalitarian and mandatory change of clothing.
Now people are judged by their clothes, focusing on the external rather than the internal person.
Maybe that person should not be given a handshake, but spat in the face.
The deception will be eliminated when the clothes are changed.
We recently saw you in the role of an urban organ grinder. A cultured city must have a hero like that.
Who better than me to be it!
en: But, maybe commercial art can be beautiful?
Now commercial art must be scrupulous, sweet, and tactful.
We are witnessing the disintegration of cultures.
People used to gather in packs, the bohemians wanted one thing, the simple ones something else.
Now everyone has split into micro-communities, it's hard to please everyone.
I'm not a hundred dollar bill to please everyone.
Now you have to think about who you want to impress.
Now, every cult hero has their 100 fans.
Thousands come to listen to Stas Mikhailov!
They will see it, the abandoned ones, there the sex-social sphere works.
There is a cultural event with 300 people attending, but 10,000 will never come. As a result, less management and less money, everything wilts away.
I have my fans, the most important thing is not to deceive them, not to ruin what you have achieved.
When I was young, I made such paintings that a collector had them hung on the wall next to Falk and Larionov.
I started with paintings, which people usually end up with.
Now they often confuse the concepts.
They say spiritual culture, consumer culture.
There is no culture in consumption, that is another story.
I am a man of yesterday's culture, I grew up under the example of artists who lived in poverty and died in poverty, they refused money just to paint pictures.
I am in favor of this culture.
En: Kirill, ¿qué le hace falta a San Petersburgo?
Good culture experts.
English: There is a concept called "Cultural Officer".
But not all of them can dedicate themselves to culture.
When the kings were right, everything was different; the kings may not have understood the culture very well, but they knew it was necessary to keep the right experts in place.
In Moscow there are now very good consultants.
We have people in St. Petersburg who could very well be experts, but they are closed off, because higher level experts are needed to properly assess them and open up their path.
Now subjective personal taste is thriving.
En: Erarta es lo mismo, pero con la diferencia de que admiten abiertamente que no toda la obra moderna es aceptada, por lo que algunos artistas tienen que buscar otros museos.
en: What does St. Petersburg mean to you?
Es: San Petersburgo no es una capital cultural. Moscú tiene mucha más cultura y ofrece un terreno más fértil.
But it is hard for art to grow on our stones.
We need a cultural landscape and now we have more writers than readers, this is not good.
In Europe there are a lot of curious people going to exhibitions and concerts.
In our case, this class is minuscule.
We need to make art fashionable again, like it was at the beginning of the last century.
The project will be carried out with a grant from St. Petersburg.
Giving birth in space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or killer asteroid impact.
Space caravans with humans onboard set off in search of a replacement planet.
en: The main question to preserve humanity is: How to continue the species in a state of weightlessness or on the same replacement planet?
I think there is little to choose from.
In fact, only two are true planets that can be colonized, at least hypothetically.
en: "These are Venus and Mars," says the head researcher of the State Astronomical Institute, Sternberg P.K. (IAES), Vladimir Surdin.
But if the conditions on Mars are better for life, the surface temperature on Venus is 500 degrees.
You can only live at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
The issues of reproduction in space were first addressed with flora.
It has been half a century since experiments with plants were carried out.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from terrestrial varieties.
After that came insect breeding in orbit, small fruit flies, Drosophila.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to test how embryos develop in a weightless environment.
We get a normal chick as a result.
But then the problems start.
en: Vladimir Sychev, the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences, explains that "the problem is that this chick has to find support, it has to keep on its own feet and start to move".
Without finding support, the chicks were flipping randomly.
After 10 hours with the newborns, a total atrophy of the instincts occurred.
The chicks did not react to the light or sound.
And the misfortune was that after four days they simply died.
"We managed to hatch the chicks twice, but then we gave up because it was impossible to work there with them," Vladimir Sychev comments on the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last time a "mini-ark" of biological specimens flew into orbit was 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
However, on the Bion biosatellite only species of the same sex will travel.
There was an experiment with rats, which were sent into space already with fetuses.
Nothing supernatural was found at first.
English: "This was precisely in the biosatellites, but this was a unique experiment, and studies like this must be carried out," comments Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats had offspring.
However, the issue of reproduction has yet to be addressed directly in space.
It is a difficult challenge.
Animals, when losing their usual habitat, simply cannot fulfill their mating instinct.
The man, however, unlike small animals, can in principle.
Humans have abstract reasoning and are capable of creating an appropriate emotional background.
Similar experiments are not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been traveling to space for over 50 years.
Tereshkova faced the greatest risk.
The most precious thing humanity has is the female body.
Our seagull flying, and no one on Earth could say: if it is after a flight to space.
Can she have a baby after this flight?
After all, no one has answered this question," comments aerospace veteran Vakhtang Vachnadze.
In June 1964, only a year after her spaceflight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The girl's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second female cosmonaut, Svetlana Savitskaya, who twice went into orbit and even worked in open space, had a son.
However, the risk persists.
We are few, the astronauts who have had successful long flights are few, and a healthy generation is growing.
"And if more can be said, it is even dangerous in orbital flights," summarizes the cosmonaut pilot, Hero of the Soviet Union, Hero of Russia, Valery Polyakov.
However, humanity must seek out some new pathways in biotechnology, radiation protection, and creating artificial gravity.
The Hydro-Laboratory of the Cosmonaut Training Center is a mandatory stage in preparation for flight.
In zero-gravity conditions, astronauts practice their space work skills.
Water simulates weightlessness.
For an adult, water is a comfortable, yet still hostile environment, but for a newborn baby, it is their native element.
The small amphibious men seem to confirm that life on land originated from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that the baby is in the amniotic fluid inside its mother for approximately 9 months, as it will be easier for them to adjust to water afterwards.
In principle, this makes sense, because from the moment of birth until the first bath only two weeks pass.
"This is too little to forget something," says Marina Aksenova, a newborn swimming instructor.
In summary, if weightlessness is a more natural state for a newborn, for women gravity, the force of gravity, is necessary.
In zero gravity, abdominal and pelvic muscles deteriorate quickly, reducing the ability to expel the fetus.
Well, we'll skip that, relying on stimulating action for labor.
It is possible, of course, to give birth in a special chamber, it will push you through.
English: "And then what?", Valeri Polyakov asks himself this original question.
en: Furthermore, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without the sensation of gravity, the body does not generate the skeleton or the muscular system.
It is impossible to dress a newborn in an astronaut training suit, as with adults, in orbit.
Just deprive him of what is vital to him.
en: "And this experiment that we are going to do together, by allowing the birth of a child in a strange environment, will lead to us bringing to Earth a disabled person, a totally unsuitable person," predicts Igor Pestov, head of the bioethics committee of the Institute of Biomedical Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
For now, the birth of children in space is a theoretical matter.
En: However, in time this will be a reality, when humans in their ships head to a distant planet that will be home to their space-born children.
NKÚ Chief: The inspection of the "švarc" system has not found the responsible politician.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has good inspectors and quality legislation, although its implementation is lagging.
Miloslav Kala, Vice President of the Supreme Audit Office (NKÚ), stated this in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
en: "The law will never be perfect," but its application must be correct. "This is, in my opinion, what we are lacking," thus describing the current situation.
Czech and German inspectors' joint inspections also come to similar conclusions.
As an example of an incorrect practice, mention Petr Nečas' attitude towards the system of being autonomous only on paper, which is known as the "švarc" system.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS (Civic Democratic Party) would not bother entrepreneurs with inspectors. So, is it forbidden or allowed?
en: Kala notes that the law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, in that case, neither the president of the government can prevent the action of the office that has the obligation to carry out such controls nor demand obligations.
At the meeting of the control committee in the Congress of Deputies, you spoke about the joint project between the Czech team and the German team, within which the legislation concerning public tenders in both countries was compared.
What exactly is it?
We have been carrying out this parallel control for about two years now.
In simplified terms: European legislation regulates how public tenders should be organized, followed by the legislation in force in each country and then the practice itself.
We have put it all together and, although the control has not yet been completed, we have obtained very interesting differences. Generally, the legislation of our country is "stricter and more complete", however, the concrete practice in some parameters is better in Germany.
It is thus confirmed that it is not enough to incorporate increasingly strict rules, but it is necessary to focus on the enforcement of the law itself.
What can this project actually contribute? What do you think are the conclusions?
Exactly this kind of common control could contribute to us stopping investing efforts in the concretion of laws, reduction and improvement of limits, even though this might not have such a positive impact.
The economy of saving means getting something suitable at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest price) in order to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But just because we reduce the limit of allocations does not mean we will achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much "paperwork", those who want to look for flaws in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You are speaking about the issues of our country with the transfer of legislation regulating the practice of public tenders.
en: How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKÚ or is it organized differently?
As for the offices, such as the NKÚ, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Audit) operates there, with an organization similar to ours, with a college as well, the only difference is that in their case it is structured somewhat differently, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
en: Competencies are also to some extent analogous, however, since Germany has a federal organization, the audit courts are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only audit federal money, which we here call state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the regions and municipalities, in Germany, are monitored by the Federal Court of Audit.
Is local legislation simpler than ours?
Generally, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data. Nevertheless, Germany remains a model in some aspects, but it cannot be precisely stated in what it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
No, definitely not, but I repeat, I don't like to make these kinds of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries we take as models must face a great number of problems.
If it weren't so, it wouldn't be of any benefit to them to collaborate with our office, don't you think?
What did the amendment to the law on public tenders mean for your Office? Is there any way in which its impact can be seen?
Taking into account that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we conduct ex post checks, there is a certain delay required.
We are currently observing in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new "non-economic risk detection" tool, through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are corrected and similar.
Do you think the passing of this law is beneficial or does it create more of a bureaucratic mess?
I believe this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The issue that may arise is that the regulations "tighten" and become impossible to comply with.
Under the previous regulations, the persons in charge were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programs of the regional council), and any law not respected in the field of public tenders meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to toughen the law in this way?
No, I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal mistake, which has no impact on decision-making.
This type of system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
en: How do we get out of this?
We will see where this journey we have started will take us.
The Prime Minister recently declared that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, in reference to the fact of being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system prohibited or allowed?
Law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the Prime Minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and enforce obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say we'll act like nothing happened.
In public procurement law, the regulations are quite strict in terms of how one must act formally. And that is how it should be in order to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its implementation must be correct. That is, in my opinion, what we are lacking.
The roads have patches of ice, but for the most part they are passable.
In several places in the Czech Republic, roads are covered with ice and snow.
Although most roads are passable, caution must be taken on some of them.
Karlovy Vary Region
Today in the morning the roads in the Karlovy Vary region were passable, but had patches of ice and snow.
The temperature is dropping and will range between five and ten degrees below zero. The thermometers will rise slightly during the day.
It has stopped snowing in the region and in the low areas the layer of snow is thin.
In contrast, snow reaches almost 30 centimeters on the peaks of the Metal Mountains.
In some places visibility was still poor due to the fog, according to the information from the regional highways operations control center.
The R6 expressway and the first-category highway in the region are now open without restrictions.
However, extreme caution is recommended, especially on some bridges whose surface may be icy and slippery.
Likewise, all second and third category roads, including mountain roads, are also passable.
Nevertheless, in some of them there are still stretches with remains of ice and packed snow.
It is necessary to increase attention on the road, especially in the higher areas.
The Pardubice and Hradec Králové Region
In some roads of Eastern Bohemia there is a risk of frost and in higher areas and in the mountains a layer of snow may have formed on the roads, according to the Roads and Highways Directorate in its pages.
Road workers are warning drivers about the danger of ice patches forming, especially in higher areas of the Pardubice region.
en: Frost can occur in the vicinity of Lanškroun, Ústí nad Orlicí, Poličky, Svitav, and Vysokého Mýta, and especially on secondary and tertiary roads.
The highways I/43 and I/34 in Svitav have been chemically treated.
Snow is especially on the roads of the Krkonoše and Orlické hory mountains.
There is a layer of packed snow on the higher areas of the roads in the municipalities of Rychnov nad Kněžnou and Trutnov.
In the Eastern Bohemia area, the sky will be between clear and partly cloudy today, with no precipitation.
The temperatures will generally range between three below zero and one degree positive, a weak wind will blow.
The Pilsen Region
The roads in the Pilsen region are passable this morning, although extreme caution should be exercised and one must adapt to the weather.
In the early morning hours there will be frost, temperatures will range between three and nine degrees below zero.
After the snowfall and the subsequent drop in temperatures, some roads could also be covered in ice.
In some places drivers will encounter fog, but visibility will gradually improve.
This is what is inferred from the information from the regional highway operations control center.
The D5 highway is almost unrestrictedly passable, although extreme caution is recommended, especially on the stretch between kilometer 80 and 131.
Most major highways have a dry, ice-free surface.
In the area of the Pilsen and Tachov border road with Germany there may be stretches with ice plates.
The secondary and third-category roads are wet, so in this case, patches of ice are also warned of.
Drivers should be more cautious, especially on less-traveled roads in the Šumava area.
Olomouc Region
Drivers heading to the higher areas of the Olomouc region will encounter partially melted snow.
After the chemical treatment, there was still snow in the Červenohorské port and on the road towards Videlský kříž.
Road workers cleared the snow during the night; three centimeters of snow accumulated on the Šumper highway, according to the road administrators.
In the rest of the region, most roads are passable without restrictions.
In the highest areas of the Šumper road, there are still remnants of snow.
Drivers at the Červenohorské port will encounter partly melted snow heading towards Jeseník, confirmed an employee of the Šumper Road Administration to ČTK today.
On the ground and at night, their colleagues also came to Jesenická, and after the chemical treatment, the trails in the higher areas are now cleared and wet.
On the Olomouc road the lanes are passable without restrictions, on the Šternberská road drivers should drive with caution on the forest sections, where the lanes remain wet.
The Ústí nad Labem Region and the Liberec Region
Road operators in Northern Bohemia have reported complications on various stretches early this morning.
Except for a few places where it has snowed or frozen, according to the police database the mountain road between Telnice and Knínice in the Ústí nad Labem region is closed.
Temperatures remain below zero, even in the lower areas, so ice and snow obviously remain on the road. In the lower areas, especially in the southeast of the Czech mountain range, however, there are no problems and the roads are generally dry.
No service complications have been reported at this time.
Road operators have warned of ice in the vicinity of Štětí.
According to meteorologists, conditions have been ideal during the night. Rain and melting snow are expected during the day, and the sky will be clear and icy at night.
Unfavorable conditions have been announced on I/13 highway at the border between Ústí nad Labem region and Liberec region from the main roads.
The road between Telnice and Knínice had to be closed due to the branches of the trees that had bent over the road under the weight of the snow.
Simon Ornest: We want to accumulate positive energy at our concerts.
It is said that the end of the world is coming in less than a month, what do you think about it?
It's just one of many other alarmist news stories that we like to cling to.
We in The Tap Tap music group like to joke about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that can gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to prevent it.
Additionally, in December you are organizing a really original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
This is a state-sponsored charitable act that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar ending on December 21st at 11:10am.
Yesterday, on December 20th at 9 PM, we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end approximately at the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we all forged the project together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state we will leave the world to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, t-shirts, bags and original keychains against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap group, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, titled "End of the World, Canceled".
Is it currently popular on YouTube, can it be heard at benefit concerts?
Yes, of course, and it will be the last one, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
All performers will sing it together at the three concerts.
The anthems will be linked together simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomas Hanak wrote the lyrics for this song and plays the lead role of Jesus in the music video, where Xindl X also sings...
How did this collaboration come about?
We work together with other personalities from the Czech cultural scene, in addition to organizing many charity events and concerts...
We are putting all our effort into participating in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the money raised from the concerts against the end of the world be used for?
We completed the equipment for the barrier-free Studeo educational center for the sixth consecutive year in partnership with the Tap civil association at Jedličkův ústav.
The students of Jedličkův ústav school regularly receive visits from teachers with whom they do fun and interesting activities.
en: Students do not have enough financial resources to pay the teachers and we are making an effort to make it possible.
In the context of the completion of the works at Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
At each concert, multiple groups and performers perform.
en: What are the selection criteria?
We are trying to develop a program that is attractive to all generations, including children.
In Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform.
For more detailed information, you can check out www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar "spectacular action" planned for the future?
In May, we will be performing for the first time at the Prague Spring Festival, so we will surely be preparing an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and, personally, taking advantage of being in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are anything but minimalistic, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London, and Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
en: There are five members in electric wheelchairs, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
en: Nevertheless, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which still amazes me.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned from, everything went smoothly.
Going abroad allows you to compare different societies' attitudes towards people with disabilities and other aspects.
en: What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is still a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, and it is still not common for someone to travel alone in an electric wheelchair in the city center.
Something as common as giving priority to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator is not common there.
Fortunately, a civil association has been created that strives to bring attention to the issues of people with disabilities.
What aspects should we take example from more advanced countries?
We are behind in many aspects...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and betterment of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid, it is very common for people with a severe disability to travel independently in public and be able to go to the service, the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to actively participate in social life, in this respect, with The Tap Tap we are a bit ahead!
A respectful and barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes for eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians, or lawyers to emerge, everything will truly begin to change.
So far, there are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
English: The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered Jedličkův ústav as an educator, where I had many young people around me who wanted to do something.
Since I am a musician, I play the saxophone among other instruments, and I founded an amateur band with a colleague.
With time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič said, it got a bit out of hand (laughter).
However, popularity didn't come until these last few years, am I wrong?
It is true that we were greatly helped by connecting with famous singers and also actively working to promote the group.
We came to the conclusion that work that is not seen is as if it does not exist.
Thanks to the aid from the European Union, we are able to afford quality teaching staff, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that was there, that something can be done differently.
The entertainment world is full of things that look alike.
It makes sense, in its own way, that all new things are met with caution and take a long time to be accepted.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare to say that The Tap Tap is one of them.
Someone's first impression of us is clearly compassion, it is a natural reaction...
But compassion is completely unnecessary because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings suffering from which we should have compassion.
People are capable of living a full and developed life, provided, of course, they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something works out well for people with disabilities, then it is not only a step forward for them, but for society as a whole.
Did the fact that you are a demanding boss, as many people describe you, help?
If we want to do a quality job, we have to be rigorous in many aspects and demand certain discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people come with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds, and when they find out they have to attend rehearsals for two days, go to the audition, and spend a lot of time traveling and in concerts, their initial euphoria quickly fades away.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap group has twenty members.
How many of them were already there at the start of 1998?
en: Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, it can't be helped.
en: Whoever has the will and desire will always find the doors open.
It will be the day before the long-awaited end of the world, Thursday, December 20th, 2012 at 9 PM.
It will take place at the Incheba Arena in Prague, at Fléda in Brno, and at Plynojem in Ostrava, and 12 groups and other musicians from the Czech Republic will participate.
The three cities will connect at the end of the evening via video conference to sing together the song of the group The Tap Tap "End of the World, Cancelled".
The goal of the concert is to gather the necessary resources to fund the multi-functional equipment of the barrier-free STUDEO educational center at Jedličkův ústav in Prague, which costs 25 million Czech crowns.
The entry to the concert costs 400 CZK and children up to 12 years old have free entry with the pre-sale option at Bohemiaticket.
Poland and the Cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers from the countries of the European Space Agency held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second ESA member from the former Eastern Bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on November 12, 2008).
en: Poland began an intense collaboration with the ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaging in space flights before World War II, though their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld's conference at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on December 6th, 1933, where he presented his pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one to show interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), previously mentioned, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
en: Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known worldwide and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
In 1925, a dresina was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown and the details of the project are also unknown.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dresina or for its braking.
The information about this dresser is limited to what was reported in the press at the time.
Starting in 1933, Polish artillery began to focus on missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is evident that the research reached the stage of practical tests.
Nevertheless, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937, the prototype of a photoelectric hunter missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of engines for missiles.
Before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile technology projects for military use and coordinated all the works.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
After the war, other studies related to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problemy, reference is made for the first time to astronautics with four very extensive articles dedicated to it.
In one of them, by Professor M. Subotowicze, the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautics was proposed.
At that time, projects for artificial satellites had already been launched and it was obvious that space research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to become a member of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and in the fall of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the Vice President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA played a significant role in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) probe rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was conducted.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10th, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not exceed 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rocket air tests began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters tall and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket under development was to be the subject of actual scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission was to monitor high-altitude winds.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built between 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other in terms of the available space for scientific equipment.
The available space for volume in the Meteor-1A rocket was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters, and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The peak height for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, with its first air tests beginning in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg up to 60 km in altitude.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the research of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Suspending the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court suspended the Social Work Law.
The resolution sparked a heated debate in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing issues from a broader perspective.
In the EU, liberal economic systems, like in the globalized world, are based on the principle of increased economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in constant conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the beginning of free trade and the unrestricted and free movement of private capital, along with rampant financial speculation.
The effect of large disparities in labor costs (wages) creates economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the importation of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this "causes a decrease" in the price of the competitor with the aim of taking the largest part of the market and, in this way, increase its profit margin.
On a large scale, for most business owners, it means moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the cost of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Due to the lack of social responsibility of private capital and, therefore, its lack of responsibility for the unemployment generated by this phenomenon, the state's social spending necessarily increases.
All of this situation fosters complete disinterest from business owners to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused in their pursuit of profits.
The situation is so widely known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations in certain economies where governments of those countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially lowering the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population regardless of social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes to existing laws.
The goal is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
en: This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted rights of employees in terms of labor rights.
The result is an increasing poverty alongside the widening gap between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food distribution points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves through their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid has now reached one million.
In the context of increasing competitiveness of the German economy, a rather frequent case occurs: people employed with such a low salary that the state has to pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
An scandal of this kind related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
Practically all states in the Southern EU are leading, without a doubt, to the same situation due to their cost-saving measures. People, pressured by a drastic decline in their social standing, are forced to emigrate like in the 19th century or to barely survive on a terrible salary on the fringes of society, in the hope that one day private capital investors will come to the country.
en: Do we need to ask ourselves where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, poverty either passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African people still work for a tiny fraction of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
English: Liberal theories and media outlets assert time and again that the state should not provide capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital fiercely defends the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask oneself if private capital does not influence political progress with its selfishness and, therefore, the entire state.
Yes, in this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The evidence is the existence of powerful and omnipresent lobbies in all states in practice.
The outcome is a desperate situation manifested in the realm of corruption, in mutual favors, and in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: the state ministries, lacking financial resources, commission the drafting of bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is then approved in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not come from the people, as proclaimed in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation like the one described by Appian in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had been disintegrating for some time and administrations were being forced upon it".
In exchange for bribes, illicitly obtained favors, and assistance in financing stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unchecked and people went to the polls with their votes already prearranged... "there was no one of character who aspired to a post in the administration, so once, due to this disorganization, the state was without consuls for eight months"... "It began to be seriously discussed that the only remedy for such a grave situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"... Although Appianos thought of Pompey, Caesar rose to power and forever transformed democracy into autocracy.
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that modern society is based on selfish preferences that disregard common interests.
Private capital is not, in essence, capable of understanding and claiming the benefits of society as a whole.
The outcome is the same as it was then, an unprecedented decline of the elite with no effort made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must be sought, therefore, in the unrestrained liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
In light of the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems in favor of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, awaiting the next blow.
The truly devastating fact is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian disasters that we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and more recent history.
The suspension of the law on public tenders is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
en: This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution lies in concrete socio-political reforms, which strengthen both the state's capital participation and citizens' influence on government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society to the benefit of the state.
En Israel: el laboratorio del caos.
English: "Nothing comes from violence and nothing ever could", Sting in his song Fragile, whose chorus goes "Let's not forget how fragile we are".
"If my children did not want wars, there would be none" Gutele Schnaper, wife of Mayer Amschel Rothschild, on her deathbed in 1849.
After the last wave of violence between Israel and the Gaza Strip, there have been, as always, diverse reactions.
One side, from Israel, argues in favor of the right to self-defense and casts Palestinians in the role of terrorists. The other side supports Palestinians and alleges racism by the state of Israel, genocide perpetrated against Palestinian Arabs, and labels Israel a terrorist state.
I don't want to focus on who is to blame for the periodic massacres and who is the victim. After all, today's citizens of Israel, including the autonomous territories, were born into the current political situation and did not live through the beginnings of the violence.
My intention is to offer readers a peek behind the curtain, a look to uncover who benefits from the tensions that have been dragging on for 95 years (calculated from the Balfour Declaration in November 1917) in a small piece of land in the Middle East.
Some of my considerations are based on historical facts, others on conclusions I have reached based on my own understanding of the matter, on who or what group of people is the main driving force behind the events of modern history.
Throughout human history, the history of struggles for power has been at the forefront.
In every era we can find an Alexander the Great or a Napoleon.
But what is no longer so obvious is whether these characters always directed their steps autonomously or if there was someone behind their throne guiding their actions towards a certain goal.
We must accept that we live in an era that concentrates the wealth of the world in the hands of a few individuals and that this concentration of money and the power it implies has not been achieved in a single generation.
Among these astronomically wealthy families, one stands out as the most prominent (if there is still someone behind it, I don't know, but I wouldn't rule it out): the Rothschilds.
Not much is written about them.
Naturally.
In the 1890s they bought the first news agency (Reuters) so that their name would no longer be associated with serious criminal acts. Power and wealth, or both, provided them with protection, which always meant a strengthening for them.
They have significant stakes in almost all central banks around the world and in those countries where they are not represented, a war has been declared or is being prepared: before the attack on Afghanistan there were 7 countries, after the attack on Iraq there were 5, after overthrowing Gaddafi only four remained, but meanwhile Russia has subordinated the central bank to the Russian government.
Everyone who has tried to oppose this family has died.
Abraham Lincoln refused to renew the charter of the Rothschild's Bank of America central bank, began printing money during the Civil War, and was assassinated in 1865 at the theater.
en: JFK started printing money and wanted to suspend the Federal Reserve (FED) system and was assassinated in 1963; Congressman Louis Mc Fadden was poisoned in 1936 after wanting to sue the FED for triggering the Great Economic Crisis of 1929.
Their ambition for world power led them between 1859 - 1871 to devise a plan for three world wars, designed by the Mason Albert Pike, decorated with the 33rd degree.
The first war aimed to eliminate the large monarchical states across Europe; the second sought to eliminate colonial supremacy, especially of Great Britain, and the third proposed to reduce the population of the earth between half a million and one billion people (such a number of slaves for their welfare and luxury would suffice and would not consume so many resources), in addition to the creation of a universal religion (ecumenism is nothing more than a pre-project for such a solution) and the definitive adoption of absolute powers.
