en: If it gets tough, call Hollywood - Argo Movie
In November 1979, a group of Islamist student protesters occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive outlook: they could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as doing so would put the trust of their allies in other countries at risk.
But the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of the theocratic regime, was beyond their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was further intensified by the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the US, their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and animosity towards Iran.
The failure in Iran decisively contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The movie "Argo" directed and acted by Ben Affleck dramatizes an episode of this story, which yielded a small success for America.
Six employees of the building escaped just before it was occupied by the embassy.
After a complicated journey, they ended up at the Canadian Embassy residence.
The CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for which it helped a covert story with a twist: they left with Canadian passports, as members of the film crew that was scouting the location in the country for the shooting of a sci-fi blockbuster.
Gender blending
The plan devised by the "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the lie seem true, articles were written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictitious production company even had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the movie has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
The Affleck movie is a unique blend of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful caper (an example could be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the movie, moods are blended together. On one hand, we find well-documented sequences from Tehran. In the credits sequence, iconic photographs of the period of the events are shown, which were captured in the same way in the movie; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes that are a bit lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: suited men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the office hallways, over the phone...
en: Ben Affleck has managed to reboot his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the subject of ridicule, has become a respected director and his manner of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little One" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck movie where the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he was raised.
Likewise, the sensitivity to capture the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed the directors of old movies above Hollywood standards.
Ben Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran is "filmed" in Canada.
The best scenes in the movie take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy takeover is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of confusion and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
En las escenas ficticias, Affleck y sus colaboradores logran un efecto similar al del equipo impostor en el bazar de Teherán.
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that a story told does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
He manages quite well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here not everything is so elegantly presented (the scene where the crisis lurks in the Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the frenzied search for its trace become a madness).
Argo's weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more screen time and are by no means the only ones in this movie.
For these reasons, Affleck's movie loses a bit of dramatic stroke, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, appreciate its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But for it to collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is enough.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas, and circus tents
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which every year presents a survey on the most absurd banking rates, has now decided to announce the competition on "the most absurd rules or ideas from the EU workshop".
We came up with the idea after the last event, the EU is planning to approve a quota of 40 percent of women in management positions in large European companies," explained Právo Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey.
en: Among the absurdities nominated is, for example, the recent decision of the European court to unify insurance policies between men and women.
So far, women have had better prices on life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk.
en: People can propose other amazing ideas from the EU workshop until the end of this year.
The election will take place at the end of February 2013, reported Nacher.
Among the controversial EU regulations is, for example, the mandatory addition of bio-components to fuel which, as a result, damages the environment; another prohibition is the use of traditional mercury thermometers only because they contain a small amount of a hazardous substance or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has contributed to the considerable increase in the price of eggs this year.
Criticism has been leveled at the de facto ban on using the term "spreadable butter" or the removal of the classic light bulb from stores.
A quality banana should be 14 centimeters in length.
The EU apparatus often takes such decisions under the pressure of one or another commercial or industrial lobby, whose requests in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (the Czech Republic, even with the threat of a veto, claims the demands of its banks).
The interests of a lobby were behind the request, for example, that higher quality bananas in the EU must have a minimum length of 14 centimeters and could not present "abnormal curvatures".
The European Commission defended itself by saying that it is only seeking to harmonize the non-homogeneous national standards which have been in place until now, making their commercialization more complicated.
The regulations regarding fruits and vegetables in the EU, despite opposition from some states, have been relaxed based on the fact that the existing directive leads to food waste.
The candidate to win the poll could be the EU prescription from last year according to which it is mandatory to warn that children under 8 years old are not allowed to inflate inflatable balloons without adult supervision.
The EU was referring here to an American study according to which, when it comes to toys, balloons are the leading cause of child death by suffocation.
en: There is also a similar restriction applicable to the use of matasuegras by children up to 14 years old.
Curious occurrences arise even in our country
en: The regulation regarding European officials is equally absurd: anyone who has an official role in the EU is not allowed to use the name Macedonia. To avoid offending Greece, one must refer to FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
Bankovnípoplatky.com server, in collaboration with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated in the survey, among some absurd proposals mentioned above, the prescription of the Union on the volume of food stocks on the territory of a Member State.
The EU determined the maximum volumes of food supplies that can be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the same day of our entry into the EU.
Afterward, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the volume set for canned mushrooms, which posed a threat of a substantial fine.
The survey organizers were also interested in the idea of paying countries without access to the sea and the idea of granting a subsidy for the application of subsidies.
These kinds of ideas did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
We are at a disadvantage due to the fact that we do not have a sea.
In Autumn 2004, then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) declared, "We are requesting compensation from the European Union."
He argued it with the fact that in our country a lot of cereal was produced and, as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had the warehouses full and it had to be exported.
According to Palas, since the Czech Republic is far from maritime ports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
In the end, the European Commission was willing to help the Czech Republic and organized a public tender for the purchase of cereals from countries without access to the sea.
The grant to receive a grant was proposed to municipalities by the Ministry for Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU). Specifically, it is intended for the drafting of grant applications from Brussels.
en: Rare prescriptions are an exception.
Member state guidelines are often the subject of criticism, yet the EU's efforts in terms of regulations and more effective functioning and development across the Union deserve our recognition, according to several experts.
Experts say the most serious problem is, for example, the collection of EU subsidies for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which Member States have secured in budget negotiations.
Czechs too have a soft spot, just like other countries in the Union, for the struggle for the right to the designation of origin of their traditional products, even though our country has not always been victorious in these battles.
After six years of disputes with Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the origin denomination of Olomouc curd cheese, but had to change the name of the national rum, whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, and it was renamed "tuzemák".
Only products made from the distillation of sugar cane can be called rum, but not those made from sugar beet.
In the official list of Protected Designations of Origin of the EU, along with the well-known feta and gorgonzola cheeses, the marzipan from the German city of Lübeck and the Parma ham, the Karlovy Vary biscuits, the carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, and even the Žatec hop variety are already included.
As protected Geographical Indications of the EU, you can be proud of the Pardubice gingerbread and the Hořice v Podkrkonoší wafers.
People want me to save the republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Okamura.
Mr. Senator, what made you decide to run for president?
It's not about being a senator or president.
If everything were well in our country, then I would not present my candidacy.
But I can no longer bear to see how stealing has been rampant in our country for the last twenty years, how thieves go unpunished, taxes are increased, and the retirement age is raised.
I had no ambitions to be a politician.
When I see something I don't like, I try to find a solution to change it.
Since I am already forty years old and my candidacy is independent, the only chance I have to change things is to run for senator or president.
The Senate has already arrived, but shortly afterwards it set off towards the presidency.
Are you not turning your back on those people who have voted for you?
I always said that my candidacy for the presidency depended on the results of the senate elections.
If I was elected senator, I later clarified that I would run for president.
But my goal is not the function; the function is the tool with which I can make my own ideas a reality.
Therefore, I need the greatest possible influence and the strongest possible mandate.
The problem is not only that we are a nation that criticizes in the bar or in front of the television, but that we trample on anyone who wants to initiate a change.
Media outlets are also to blame, as they discredit you and confuse freedom of expression with the freedom to lie.
It is said of me that I have bribed journalists or that I have been an advisor to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's talk about your ideas.
He enters the presidential race with financial theses and criminal liabilities of politicians and the declaration of property worth over twenty million.
To do this, the law must be changed.
As president, he does not have this power and only the Senate as a whole can propose laws.
How do you want to solve it?
As a citizen, I have been part of a pressure group to have the profession of guide recognized as self-employment, and we succeeded.
The problem lies in the politics: if someone comes with a good proposal, whether from the right or the left, it is deliberately rejected and this affects citizens.
As an independent candidate, I have greater potential to gain support from all parliamentary groups.
Without pigeonholing or party dogmas, I have the ability to choose something from each party that is best for our country and apply it.
Is he more of a right-wing or left-wing man?
From the Czech perspective, I get the impression that people view me as more left-wing.
For me, it doesn't matter whether it's a bit left or a bit right.
What matters to me is that we make it through.
I don't care if someone is right-wing or left-wing, I want to unite people.
I always openly support any good solution, regardless of whether the proposal comes from the KSČM or the ODS and, likewise, I will be against bad ideas.
They joke when they say you are populist.
Is he not demonstrating it with what he says?
When creating a business plan for the company, you also have certain goals and ideals.
You try to get close to them.
Some may call it populism, but all of the proposals I'm talking about already work in the world or are discussed by well-known experts.
But without the support of Parliament, only slogans remain.
With this, he cannot survive in politics in the long run.
Do you think that if you address people and speak to them, you will get, for example, criminal and financial responsibility?
I have no other choice.
Convince politicians, journalists, and civil society and try to get them on my side to achieve it.
If I were elected president, there would be no problem in organizing a live broadcast on television in which I would ask the leaders of the parliamentary parties to legitimize criminal and financial responsibility for politicians, civil servants, judges and state prosecutors.
Eventually, they would have to communicate why they do not want it.
If there is a strong character that points out disputes, pressure can be exerted in the political scene.
Let's take the direct election of the president, which has been an achievement of public pressure, as an example.
At the same time, I claim that I am only an enthusiast, not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my opinions and ideals.
I have just started in politics and am trying to get as much support as possible for my platform.
I'm trying to make it on my own, but if it doesn't work out, I'll be leaving in six years and going back to the private sector.
It sounds a bit like Okamura is going to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know that I can't do anything alone, so I have visited a number of well-known personalities to see if they might be interested in running for the Senate.
I went to see Radim Jančura, but he refused because he had a lot of work.
I have at least supported investigative journalist Jana Lorencová, who brought to light the frauds with light heating oils.
I started out on the premise that people are really dissatisfied, now I'm on the scales.
Sixty percent of the population did not go to the polls and those who did voted for the representatives of the establishment.
In the Senate, there are two of us from the independent sector.
People chose the senate, so it will be difficult to achieve changes.
However, I will defend my own ideas, such as the direct election of mayors or governors.
Are you considering forming your own party?
I haven't considered it yet because I don't have the time to check the impeccable past of each potential party member, nor do I have the money.
I don't have money for the presidential campaign, there are only 20,000 crowns in my transparent account.
en: Don't you have any money?
en: Talk about property statements, what is yours like?
I estimate my private property at around 60 million.
In Prague I have a plot of land valued at 25 million, an apartment valued at ten million, another apartment appraised at eight million, an art collection worth ten million, an Aston Martin worth about 3.5 million, a Škoda Superb valued at one million, and in the bank account I have a couple of million.
I have an Aston Martin by the way because it was my childhood dream. I always liked James Bond, who drove this car, was gallant with women and, at the same time, fought against evil and injustice.
Does he drive an Aston Martin, his property is valued at 60 million and he has no money for the campaign?
You say you want to change the republic but you don't want to put too much money of your own in.
It's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million for the campaign.
Do I have to go into debt?
I have already put 2.5 million in the campaign.
The fact that I have no sponsors shows that there is not much interest in my program.
I do not have the obligation to pay for the campaign with my own money.
The campaign expenses essentially cover what I will receive in terms of senator's salary.
But I couldn't live off of it. For example, I couldn't pay for my son's English school, which costs 30,000 crowns a month.
If I only wanted to make money, then I would not put myself forward as a candidate.
Will he continue with his business activity in order to live?
Didn't you say before that you were going to quit this activity?
This has nothing to do with a higher salary.
As promised, I have partially left my activities.
For example, my travel agency representative will be my substitute in the spring.
People would want to be the Good Samaritan who would save the republic.
But I also need to make a living.
en: How much do you usually make monthly as an entrepreneur?
en: Between 200,000 and 400,000, I keep winning.
If I were president, then I would leave the business.
