MVRDV Architecture Studio proves that true adventures are not just in the head - exemplified by the Spijkenisse Library and the recently completed "Mountain of Books" - 2 photos.
en: Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the street, says, "I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and finally there's something interesting to see."
Stefan Spermon, a IT technician at a large company located near the library, notes: "Furthermore, the building is beautiful."
But I wonder why we need a library nowadays.
We all have Internet, tablets, and e-books.
Nobody goes to those outdated libraries by choice, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom town located on the outskirts of Rotterdam that barely deserves a passing visit, holds the dubious honor of having achieved a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges represented on euro banknotes in the form of concrete miniaturas decorated with reinforced steel.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
So that is how the political leaders decided that there was only one way to improve the statistics: they had to build a library!
Dutch architect Winy Maas of MVRDV, a master of the art of bar charts and responsible for fun yet cynical buildings, took the topic with his usual serenity and attended the competition presentation in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
As the jury looked around perplexed and shrugged their shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books in Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'.
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros stands in the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office, and a couple of residential and terraced buildings.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
Additionally, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking in history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather guess a dairy farm, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But most of all, Spijkenisse now has its first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to the book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese dome.
It is true that there is an elevator that takes us right to the center of this mountainous mass, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but rather they prefer to merge with its topography with each step of their climb to the summit.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to take in with the eye, the brick-fired floor and the elegant street lamps unmistakably support the public nature of the library.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
When looking up, you can see the benches of the park, the dogs, and the children playing soccer.
Everywhere books, books, and more books.
en: Winy Maas states that usually book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the center an enormous dark room is opened, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal.
We have turned the classic spatial configuration upside down and taken the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is well utilized: in the middle are the offices, the internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center, and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
Sight, touch, and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
We wanted to work with recycled materials, explains Joop Trouborst, project leader in the city of Spijkenisse.
So this is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from farming.
For many years, plastic fabric of few millimeters thick has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a base to hold the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to achieve plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mixture of new car and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this almost 500-meter continuous route around the mountain awaits the reward: from the cafeteria not only is there a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy delicious Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the appropriate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
Despite its large glass surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology, according to Trouborst.
The heating and cooling needed are obtained from geothermal energy.
Despite the mountain of books being situated beneath a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden arches placed across the glass facade serve to provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is up to the automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to step foot in the new library.
Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
English: Similarly, Traditional Chinese Medicine professor Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She rates the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
This is intended to fill, for now, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; currently it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has struck a chord.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
I believe that thanks to our initiative, now all the inhabitants have some kind of connection with this building.
Everyone knows that their book is part of the library.
Although it is only there to adorn.
en: In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved great success in the discipline of creating an identity, which is known in specialized jargon.
Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
Regardless of how young and inexperienced they may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
en: Szabo: "Germans must take on a more leading role"
Germany abstained from voting on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather awkward diplomatic position.
German broadcaster Deutsche Welle reported earlier this week that Germany indicated it would vote against the proposal to grant Palestinian territories the status of observer state at the United Nations.
However, Berlin eventually abstained.
Why?
en: Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, due to the special relationship between the country and Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I don't think it supports the American stance either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising that took place in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Does it prove difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, that's right.
This is due to the fact that Germany is currently reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
What makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to take on a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still feeling out what their role will be, but they have already started down the path towards a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to that of countries like France or the United Kingdom.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean specifically from a German perspective?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European allies.
I believe that German foreign policy finds strong motivation in economic policy, namely in exports and its relationships with certain regions such as Russia, China, and the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other major powers and for this reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf, on the one hand.
For this reason, she must be careful not to alienate herself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't give it so much importance since it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German stance enjoys a great degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that a break as drastic as in the case of Libya has occurred.
Perhaps Germany has earned some respect with this.
In the end, all of this has only served to demonstrate that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
In contrast, the US has clearly come out in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Always these disparities have existed due to the United States' domestic policy.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding towards the European position.
But due to the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that stance.
I believe that the true disparity of opinions does not actually have the magnitude that is attributed to it.
If we analyze the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is pursuing.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relationships with Israel and the United States on the one hand with the stance of its main EU partners on the other?
I think that's exactly what makes it so difficult for Germans.
Of course it would be a bit easier for Germans if there was a coherent and homogenous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility to be part of a higher entity, but must drive things from their own position.
They are doing exactly that with the euro right now.
I believe that in the future Germany will take on a leadership role in forcing Europe to take a European stance.
en: Of course, this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I believe the Germans are clear that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international actor? Does Germany actually wish to take on a leading role?
Is it still difficult for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet gotten used to it, it always remains somewhat uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still finds it difficult to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany takes the lead, certain anti-German feelings are stirred up.
This is not easy for Germans.
It is an old problem and that is no one wants to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Seen in this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You must show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
English: US influence in European politics is decreasing more and more, but the EU is not yet filling that gap, who is left then?
Germans will have no choice but to take on a more prominent role.
Even if they don't like it, if it's unpleasant to them, or if it makes them an even more unpopular town, c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is the Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, a institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
en: Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
Protection of Brands in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese Brands
En: Armani is a globally known brand and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
en: What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name lies an officially registered denomination in China but which has nothing to do with the original companies.
Nevertheless, this enjoys protection while the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
Even then it is not clear that they will be given the right.
English: "It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer from the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in intellectual property rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case arrives at my desk.
The imitators simply add a couple of letters in order to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies also legally copy each other in the same way, as has happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opened a filing cabinet in which he kept records of the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the brand Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also made use of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that Chinese people are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights.
In big cities there are large multi-story stores dedicated solely to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he is fighting against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to benefit from a denomination that is already registered elsewhere.
en: It is referred to as "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand in Chinese.
The word originates from the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan".
Refers to women who have "caught" a wealthy man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
en: "It is detrimental to the business, we have to fight against it," demands Pattloch.
The brand is faltering, its monopolistic position is disappearing, and the damage to its image is immense.
Financial losses and legal costs of the affected sectors are in the millions, especially in the case of luxury iconic products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year, China is the third largest luxury goods market and the one growing at the fastest rate.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the trademark registry is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can be extended up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch discusses cases where the court dismissed a claim because so much time had passed that the name subject to the claim had become a "market reality".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, they may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged their brand in China," says Pattloch.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the most well-known cases have to do with graphical elements.
In 2009, Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company which has recently been acquired by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
Therefore, today Chinese people can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that strongly resembled BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction of the original.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The Beijing CTMO Trademark Office acknowledges that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to lack of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the emergency labor situation returned to normal."
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain unresolved.
Fighting against this costs a lot of money.
As is usually the case in China, the figures are astonishing.
Last year, the CTMO recorded more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China has led the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the Trademark Office.
It seems that this also applies to the number of valid logos, which amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed in royalties.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as demonstrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For over seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
The Germans have managed to stop the illegal production of imitation car parts.
The imitator has secured Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
"We have brought this situation upon ourselves because in Germany surnames are not protected," says Hanno Wentzler, President and Chief Executive Officer of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO Trademark Office also dismissed the appeal of the Munich residents.
In the two subsequent instances, Freudenberg has been vindicated, but the opposing side is still fighting the case to this day.
English: Take extreme caution.
The case has now reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it remains pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident he can resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that "the procedure is extremely costly, both in terms of money and time."
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business file has had to review records up to one hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg offered the other party a "six-figure sum in euros" in order to reach an amicable agreement, but it was unsuccessful.
en: "This shows how much we care," Wentzler states.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe.
Specifically, if the imitators secure rights over unregistered trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register the name Freudenberg in Germany for shoes and leather products.
The group has been away from this commercial area for a while, but they managed to prevent registration.
en: "We must be very careful," Wentzler states.
He and lawyer Pattloch both recommend that German companies be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark legislation, but what needs to be done is "also register in China anything that may be eligible for protection," as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the matter can end up costing much more than a simple registration.
If Freudenberg were to lose the last round of its own battle, then it would have to pay the opposing party licensing fees for its own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would get us kicked out of the market.
World AIDS Day: Dance, Sing, Help
In Heidelberg, the Imbongi Choir rehearses and in Swaziland, the orphans of AIDS are rejoicing.
The story of a bond capable of overcoming more than 8,733 kilometers of distance.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball sneakers, high heels and loafers search for the beat on the parquet floor, and find it quickly.
One, two, three, four.
en Only then do the voices of the singers (contralto, bass, tenor and soprano) begin to rise slowly, swirling, getting tangled and following each other.
Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to lose his temper as he tries to bring order with his energetic and gentle gestures.
It is Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Heidelberg Medical Psychology Institute the Imbongi choir is rehearsing a new song.
Fifty singers, ranging in age from 23 to 69, have also arrived, from the human geneticist to the housewife.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each voice of the choir has a different text and also in a foreign language barely known: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for Self-Help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS, there are approximately 34 million people worldwide infected with the HIV virus.
en: 23.5 million of them live in Southern Africa.
In Swaziland there are 245,000 AIDS orphans.
Over 40% of the population is already seropositive.
Voices for Africa has found sponsors in Germany for the 180 AIDS orphans of the village of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend secondary school.
For 15 to 20 euros a month, you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover school fees, uniforms, and guarantee a hot meal per day at the Gogo Center.
En zulú, imbongi significa "narrador de historias" o "panegirista".
Nobody in this room knows how to speak this Bantu language fluently, but they can sing.
For the past ten years, this choir has been rehearsing songs in this gentle foreign language that sometimes transports them back to their place of origin: the south of Africa.
Esitjeni, a 8,733 kilometers in a straight line from Heidelberg in northeastern Suaziland, is a village that relies on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected.
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large portion of them being children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Swaziland is affected by a high rate of HIV infection and the lowest life expectancy in the world, according to UNICEF, as exemplified by Esitjeni.
The population does not look favorably upon circumcision, a practice which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by half.
Over 40% of the inhabitants of Swaziland are carriers of the HIV virus, and dying before the age of thirty has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir discovered this hidden population, but what they saw above all were many children in the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the most important thing: food, clothing and education.
Without a school title, the possibilities in a poor country are more than scarce.
At first, it was only the commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day, all for a few euros.
However, one year later the choir founded the association "Voices for Africa" which has since professionally taken care of the AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
en: What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Among the bacterial STDs are syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, Human Papillomavirus, Genital Herpes, or Hepatitis.
English: Lice and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are more common in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five cases of syphilis registered in Germany originate from sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomoniasis, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
Heterosexual adults in the country have relatively low HIV infection rates; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections are recorded in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, Human Papillomavirus (HPV) is also added to the most common diseases among youth.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
In 2011, approximately 2,700 cases were recorded.
It is one tenth less than the previous year.
en: What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often they do not cause pain or produce other symptoms, so they are not detected.
How can one protect themselves?
En: Condoms can reduce the risk of transmission, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through uncleanliness and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend undergoing regular medical checkups, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late-term consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations, and last but not least, the fees the choir charges for its performances throughout Germany, they manage to raise quite a bit of money.
"We have already sent a total of 200,000 euros to Esitjeni," proudly states Annette Lennartz, president of the association.
In the village of Zodwa Dlamini, a self-confident woman with leadership skills manages the money sent from Germany.
She takes care of making sure orphans find a good home, for example with one of the grandmothers.
Zulu-speaking women elders, known as "gogos", are the pillars of the community.
Some of them have up to 14 orphans in their care, they provide a roof over their heads and make sure the children attend school every day punctually and dressed in their uniforms.
en: Those who have no one are under the protection of Khanyisile, a single woman who, like the two cooks who are responsible for cooking every day for more than 200 hungry children, receives a salary from the association.
Additionally, "Voices of Africa" has launched a sewing school, built two chicken coops, and in collaboration with the US health organization PSI, has managed to get many of the village's inhabitants tested for HIV.
This is not something obvious, since, despite how widespread this disease is across the country, it is not usually openly discussed.
A king with 14 wives
Annette Lennartz states that AIDS is an absolute taboo because it has to do with sexuality.
Something strange in a country where the king officially has 14 wives.
The last absolute monarch of Black Africa, King Mswati III, is known for his opulent and excessive lifestyle.
Polygamy instead of democracy.
This form of life not officially accepted is largely responsible for the rapid spread that HIV virus has experienced in the last decades.
But it is also due to the countless itinerant workers who travel across the country and take it with them wherever they go.
According to Annette Lennartz, "condoms are available for free on every corner, but they are hardly ever used.
en: It is another culture, here they only accept skin-to-skin contact.
To promote cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two or three years throughout Southern Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, fighting spirit, hope and confidence in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost part of the African continent still remember from the era of apartheid.
A bus full of white people singing songs in a black language; not only does this bring an excellent atmosphere and much joy, but it has also managed to bring a few tears to some angry border soldiers.
They always take the journey to Esitjeni, where the singers visit the sponsored children.
Despite this small population barely appearing on maps, the valley of the Ezulweni River is well known.
English: "Come to Esitjeni, there the light shines," say the people of the place.
After traveling the 8,733 kilometers in a straight line back to Heidelberg to the rehearsal rooms on Bergheimer Street full of singers marking the beat, one realizes that it is also possible to see its light shine from there.
en: The NASA discovers ice on Mercury
The Messenger probe has found evidence of ice on Mercury.
Probably the ice layer has a thickness of up to 20 meters.
The NASA, the American space agency, has provided evidence of the existence of ice on Mercury.
Despite being the closest planet to the sun, there is also frozen water there, as three studies published Thursday in the specialized journal "Science" show.
The Messenger probe has reportedly found evidence that a layer of ice has formed in the area of the planet that is perpetually in shadow.
It looks like this one has at least 30 centimeters and probably even up to 20 meters of thickness.
Water presumably comes from comets or, more likely, asteroids that collided with Mercury in the past.
No one links the discovery of ice to the possibility of life on the planet, says Messenger probe chief investigator Sean Solomon.
The temperature on Mercury can reach up to 426 degrees Celsius.
However, the findings could help to shed light on how water and other components of life have reached other areas of the solar system.
Unnoticed by the inhabitants of planet Earth, probes, telescopes, and small robots like Phoenix are devoted to exploring the depths of the universe.
Every now and then they send images back to Earth: small windows into the vastness of space.
The image comes from a camera developed by German researchers from the Max Planck Institute.
The eight planets that make up our solar system, in addition to the dwarf planet Ceres.
