This star-forming region, unromantically dubbed by scientists as W5, was discovered by the Spitzer Telescope in the constellation of Cassiopeia, at a distance of 6,500 light years.
This iridescent image of a dying star was taken by NASA's Spitzer Telescope.
The donut-shaped ring is composed of the material that the star spews out in its extinction process.
In the vast Trifid Nebula, 5,400 light years away from Earth, new stars are forming from gas and dust.
The NASA Spitzer Telescope took this photo of the galactic star-forming region.
