One of the largest and clearest photographs taken by the Hubble Telescope: the Whirlpool Galaxy.
Depending on the hues, some images of spiral galaxies become true works of art.
The image released by the European Southern Observatory shows the Trifid Nebula located several thousand light years away in the constellation of Sagittarius.
The name Trífida comes from the Latin term "trifidus" (divided into three), since dark dust lanes divide the hot heart of this star-forming region into three lobes.
Astronomers in the constellation of Ophiuchus were able to photograph evidence of a cosmic collision: 400 million light years away from Earth, the cores of two galaxies in the process of merging rush towards each other, eventually colliding irrevocably.
This formation of stars was captured by the Hubble Telescope in the spiral galaxy M83.
Those who do not like technical abbreviations can refer to it by its nickname, the Southern Grinder.
The Hubble Space Telescope photograph shows a section of the Iris Nebula in the constellation of Cepheus.
The nebula located 1,400 light-years away is composed of dust particles that are between ten and one hundred times smaller than the dust particles we can find in a house.
This image was created from optical images and X-rays taken by various telescopes.
Show a ring of black holes located 430 million light years away from Earth.
