Do you intend to deprive the judiciary of its power?
Indeed, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members in a 15-hour overnight session, are truly concerning.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
en: But what does "principles" mean?
This was and remains open to interpretation and it appears that Islamists are going to take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the legal leeway that comes with it, to impose a stricter interpretation of Sharia.
This is at least what is suggested by a new article added: in all matters related to Sharia, it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power throughout Sunni Islam.
It doesn't have to be this way, but this could mean that the clergy would control legislation, something which - in fact - would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft of the constitution is open to interpretation.
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
Under Mubarak's dictatorship, these courts served to exercise a harsh repression on the opposition.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were held in military prisons.
As stipulated in the draft, the State shall protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morality and values".
It is such an imprecise legal formulation that, with the help of this article, state institutions could even control the contents of cinema and literature.
Speaking plainly, it is nothing but censorship.
No article explicitly states equality between men and women.
Instead, another forbids offending or slandering the Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is not clear what constitutes an offense and how it should be sanctioned.
en: Just as dubious is the formulation that prohibits "offense to persons"
Is a cartoon of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
It is a matter of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Mursi for his signature and, according to his words, will be presented to the Egyptians "very soon" to be put to a referendum.
English: The revolution has returned.
The opposition has been uniting against the dominance of the Islamists for weeks.
Ten thousand people gathered in an unusual harmony on Friday afternoon in Tahrir Square in Cairo and vowed to make the Act fail before it can come into effect.
en: Hamdin Sabbahi, who is in third place on the presidential election lists, states that "The revolution has returned and we will end up victorious".
English: Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, declared that the draft of the constitution should be "in the dustbin of history".
He accused Morsi's followers of wanting to lead a "coup against democracy" through Twitter.
English: Opponent Jasser Said stated, "When the referendum is called, we will go to his palace and overthrow him."
"We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers has not yet been avenged," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali.
Several judges announced that they did not wish to oversee the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
en: The Quran is our constitution.
The well-organized Muslim community made a call to hold a counter-demonstration, not in Tahrir Square but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, in front of the University of Cairo.
Many women covered in a veil and supporters of Salafists took part in it, shouting: "The people demand the application of divine law".
They demanded that Morsi "clean up the country," while proclaiming: "the Quran is our constitution."
en: A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where it all began, would have provoked a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It is evident that supporters of Mursi did not want to risk something like this happening.
The Muslim Brotherhood stated that both those who oppose the draft constitution and those who support it had expressed their views loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people decide in the ballot box which direction the country should take.
In this sense, it appears that the draft of the Islamists has a guaranteed majority.
en: "The phrase 'Human Rights' does not even appear."
en: Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process which should have actually lasted until February and included all social forces.
en: This 48-year-old lawyer specialized in human rights and president of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brothers when they were detained in prison or had to face a trial during Mubarak's dictatorship.
He supported Human Rights not because he shared the same ideology, but because for him Human Rights are indivisible.
For this reason, he was beaten, convicted, and imprisoned.
"And now the expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear in the new constitution," laments a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The expansion of Mursi's powers to the three branches of the state caused this lawyer to resign.
en: The measures taken are blatant violations of the rules of democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
Saeda laments that instead of strengthening civil society, the president has abolished it.
en: However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
She feels abandoned, even by the international community, which watches the ideological struggle taking place along the Nile with a mix of curiosity and tension.
This could backfire on you.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns, "You are creating a monster you won't be able to control."
Norwegian Rakfisk: The smelliest fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the success of the country has something to do with its appetite for an extremely smelly fish?
Take a selection of overly cured cheeses.
Put them in the middle of a mountain of wet and dirty football clothing.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It is snowing. The scenery is spectacular and that smell, always present, lingers in the air.
Rakfisk is a trout salted and left to ferment in water for up to a year, depending on how pungent you prefer it.
As the darkness falls and the temperature drops, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most captivating of delicacies.
En: "Eat it raw and then down a shot of aquavit in one go," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of Rakfisk," responsible for organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking large amounts of the drink in one gulp.
Havard claims that some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk.
The drink can kill the smell.
I'm trying some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it's not bad; it's not much different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different era, when poverty plagued Norway and when, before refrigeration existed, fish was stored during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is well fermented, it is taken out and, obviously with the senses inactive due to the alcohol, it is eaten.
Just one generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and primarily emigrated to the United States.
Currently, the population is rapidly increasing; over 13% are immigrants, drawn by the abundance of job opportunities, high wages, and a comprehensive social services system.
A stream of inhabitants from Sweden, the old rival and until not too long ago wealthier than Norway, is coming to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered an important, albeit quite smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes that can be bought.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer or a sandwich will cost you a whopping 10€ ($14) each.
Norway rarely appears in the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it that way.
Here, people are still reluctant to utter the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
In its place, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22nd incident".
Norwegians find it hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of such cruelty and murder.
Much of Norway's current wealth is due to the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she passes trays of rakfisk and, with her long blonde hair and her striking blue eyes, she embodies the image of Norwegian wellbeing.
We are, as you say, prudent people.
Their English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
We don't like to boast, we don't like showiness.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; all but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone else was recklessly spending money they didn't have in the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept its wallet tightly shut.
en: "As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we're happy," says Anna.
He adds with a hearty laugh, "And eat rakfisk!"
I'm in the snow queuing up to get something to eat; I've had enough rakfisk already.
Now an elk burger is certainly something different and quite delicious to savor.
But at night, that smelly fish returns.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of many venues hosting a rakfisk dinner where guests vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests their noses the most.
A television has gone live to a presenter wearing a bow tie and surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
It looks like the Eurovision Contest.
English: "What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
Here is our score, Harvard.
There are laughs and applause.
A man falls off the chair, perhaps overcome by aquavit.
Maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
en: Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
As incoming Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant examines the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his population.
The traffic in Mexico City is especially bad right now.
In a city that is already congested under the best of circumstances, a steel barricade has been set up since Monday, blocking several of the main roads leading into the city and causing massive chaos on the roads.
The goal, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching the parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential sash and take office as the nation's leader.
He is facing a complicated task.
Mexico has achieved good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is immersed in a war against drug trafficking which has already claimed about 60,000 lives in six years.
en: Mr. Peña Nieto explained to US President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week that "my government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence".
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to reach that goal.
Before shaking hands with the President of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as Governor of his home state of Mexico.
A heavily populated and rapidly growing state surrounding the capital; opinions on the new leader are divided in this territory where he used to move around.
A sincere man
In the idyllic town of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is fondly remembered.
Its residents credit it with the growth of tourism in the area and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city one can drive on one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new highways, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked and potholed roads that were rehabilitated.
en: You can also see signs with your name at the entrance of a modern sports complex and an impressive interactive museum about climate change.
His friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a deputy from Mr. Peña Nieto's PRI party, says, "We trust that he will be able to make a real and lasting change."
Particularly with regard to security and economy, we anticipate the interesting and genuine change that our country so desperately needs.
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted by Vicente Fox in 2000.
The deputy Olvera admits that, after 12 years away from the Presidential Palace of Los Pinos, within the party there are high expectations regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
Reject also the rating that the opposition makes of the lack of essence of the new president.
He is a very honest man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an outstanding statesman and, above all, he is a person who knows how to listen.
However, on the other side of the state, that is not the impression many people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobblestone streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden beneath elevated highway overpasses, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
The problems of the municipality are also tough and urban.
At the beginning of this year, the intervention of the military was requested to help in the fight against drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods and violence against women is especially serious.
On a deserted plot of land next to a landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left abandoned in just the last two years.
Over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a much higher rate than Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for its violence and a place synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Critics of Mr. Peña Nieto say, at best, that he did not know how to address the issue of femicide while in office.
Critics of the administration accuse them of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the rundown neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make an effort to hold back her tears as she shows me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes her partner murdered her.
When I arrived at her house, it looked like they had cleaned her body, Mrs. Buendía remembers.
There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already set in.
As her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana watches from the walls, alongside a cross bearing a single word: Justice.
en: However, that is exactly what the family says has been denied to them.
The authorities of the state have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a complainer.
They want one to simply accept what they say and keep quiet.
But that cannot be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence," he states.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will come accompanied by a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to prioritize them during his term.
"I hope he will be the same kind of president he was when he was governor," says PRI Deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not report mistreatment, according to prosecutors.
Prosecutors are attempting to address the allegations of abuse of Bradley Manning during his imprisonment.
The trial focuses on Manning's period in the military prison at Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants the case to be dismissed based on the fact that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The soldier of the army is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in US history, missed multiple opportunities to report the mistreatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During the questioning that the prosecution conducted of Manning at a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Commander Ashden Fein of the prosecution stated that the records of the weekly visits of unit officers Manning received during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing held in response to the defense's request to dismiss the case due to the harshness of Manning's imprisonment and the fact that it had already served as sufficient punishment, came one day after Manning had testified that he had contemplated suicide while in custody.
The Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is charged with stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks released the material on the internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
On Friday's view, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his imprisonment at the Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked questions to Manning and recorded his answers.
On Friday, when Fein asked about the forms, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment he received from the wardens as "excellent" and the treatment he received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
No forms showed any reports of mistreatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
en: Manning replied that he had expressed his concern about certain matters and that the officers visiting him had discussed those issues and had indicated that they would be addressed, but that they had not recorded those matters in the record.
en: Manning said, "They wrote 'without incident' (after talking about the issues) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I didn't mention any problems."
Judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not reported the treatment he received during the meeting that took place in January 2011 with a board tasked with examining the suicide intentions he had expressed in a form months prior.
en: Manning stated that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime he was under.
The military said they had placed him under that restrictive regime, one degree below that of suicide watch, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
I wanted the top brass to know that I was okay and (wanted) to get out of the injury prevention mode... so I could enjoy what, in my opinion, is a better quality of life, said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia in July of 2010.
He said he had contemplated suicide in Kuwait and that he had once passed out due to the heat.
She said that not being allowed to know what was happening to her or what was going on in the outside world was very distressing.
en: "My world was reduced to just Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Manning stated that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without any company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some flip-flops, some clothes, and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to keep moving all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning stated that he always had a light from outside shining into his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the warders couldn't see his face when he turned over at night, they would wake him up to turn over again.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about the treatment Manning was receiving.
English: Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an assertion he had made in his Thursday statement, that he had been forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell and was then made to stand naked during a morning count in front of guards and other inmates.
Manning testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's questioning on Friday, Manning said he inferred from the guard's order that he should drop the blanket he could have used to cover himself, but he acknowledged that nobody had ordered him to drop it.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before in an attempt to demonstrate to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic from his underwear or his flip-flops to self-harm but that he had not done so.
He testified that his underwear, slippers, and glasses had been taken from his cell that night.
Their lawyers are hoping that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be found guilty in the court-martial, which is scheduled to start at the beginning of next year.
The defense stated that they intend to have Manning plead guilty to lesser charges and contest other charges deemed too extreme.
It is expected that the hearing will resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the application standards for all detainees under maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include aiding the enemy, illegally causing the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If found guilty of all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
Many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; they say it reminds them of Mexicans from those difficult times.
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had barely stepped off the concourse and arrived at the immigration processing area and I was already completely confused.
Signs indicated the way to two lines: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners".
I stayed there for a few seconds not sure which way to go.
Growing up in Central California, I have been called "Mexican" my whole life.
It is ethnic shorthand, in the same way my friends from Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends from New York self-identify as "Italian".
en: I eventually settled on "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
In my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish. Well enough to get by during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native speaker and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my US passport and got in line for foreigners.
I thought of that moment this week when Mexico's President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On today's agenda, as is always the case when the leaders of these two countries meet, was immigration, drugs, and trade.
En: Peña Nieto was eager to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy as well, one of the reasons why it is now so likely for a Mexican to stay in Mexico rather than venture to the United States.
He wants to partner with the United States and Canada to create a North American trading bloc similar to the European Union.
Additionally, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting against drug cartels in Mexico, though he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of its territory at gunpoint.
For Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So whenever a US official says anything that even slightly criticizes Mexico, you start to hear complaints, both in the press and among Mexican elites, about how Americans are infringing on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
en: The sons of Moctezuma stand ready for war.
For Mexico, the relationship with the over 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States is truly a challenge.
Shall we talk about resentment?
There is a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was someone, perhaps a father or mother or one of the grandparents, who had the door of opportunity closed to them in Mexico and had to move north.
Most of the time, that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, low educational level, from a poor village, etc.
We are your descendants and we are loyal to you.
No to Mexico.
Despite the fact that we may be living the American Dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we must never forget that what we are living is the American Dream, and not the Mexican Dream.
It is possible that sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It is for the United States.
Additionally, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us as if we are of a lower class that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And now we wouldn't find ourselves trapped behind this curtain of silk, living well in the United States but, still, like lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally came to the United States when she was a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more firmly who they are and the latter are bothered by this.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel like they don't belong to either.
We love listening to the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also to Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
In the United States, we are considered Mexican.
Now, to complicate things even further, from what I have heard on my travels, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised "ambassadors" of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit that country and we would urge political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course...
en: That's not going to happen.
There is too much resentment.
And with the wage inequality, rampant corruption, and drug-related violence, many of us are not so sure that it is a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be on your own with this idea, friends.
It is fair.
If some Mexicans are still not ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they must accept that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated much less time ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we are more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could be a unlikely foundation for peace.
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another spill of blood that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amidst the futile and all-too-familiar debates over who started it first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, Israel's metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
Despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians seem to be stuck in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in pieces, whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional turmoil.
Maybe this will make their struggle even bloodier than before.
However, there are reasons to think that their deadlock situation could be broken.
A war that is neither won nor lost
At first glance, optimism seems currently very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21st is maintained, the clashes this week have strengthened the hawks on both sides.
en: Hamas leaders, the Islamic movement that has governed Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, despite Gaza having taken a beating.
Despite killing some of its leaders and squeezing 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza into one of the most miserable and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to defeat Hamas.
en: Hamas is actually gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals from Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
Additionally, Hamas leaders may come to the conclusion that time is on their side.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made wealthy and powerful allies.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced the cause of Hamas. So too has Qatar, one of the wealthiest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Hamas' exultant members say that the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the party-militia Hezbollah dominates, through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist tendency could overthrow Bashar Assad, all the way to Jordan, where Hamas' allies are threatening the king.
Above all in the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and influential of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
En: Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time for Hamas.
In contrast, the Muslim Brotherhood are cousins of Hamas and their leaders rely more on public opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, it is possible that Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even by Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, the hard-line faction of Israel will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, Hamas has been put in its place.
The Iron Dome missile defense system of Israel has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep more peacefully... for some time.
As for diplomacy, the United States is showing more firmness than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
en: Above all, Israel has prospered. Especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a Prime Minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have ended the lives of around 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, partly due to the barrier that runs through the West Bank, the main piece of land aspiring to become the state of Palestine, and protects the Jewish settlements that continue to grow despite being deemed illegal under international law.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined a group of an even tougher line led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22nd elections, is in a good position.
Why pamper those twisted Palestinians by giving them their own state?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets like their compatriots in Gaza have done?
It is better to keep them behind that wall and give them a good hit if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard-liners will prevail, although the Arab Spring could disrupt their calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere may not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defense budget is greater than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the superpower in the region will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
The fact that pragmatic Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to secure the ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
English: Israelis should also think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, denying Palestinians their right to self-determination creates a powder keg that will one day explode in the territories occupied by Israel, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already eroding democracy in the Jewish state and demographics are worsening the situation as the Arab population increases.
The bloody military operations against Gaza every two or three years to repel Hamas will pay an increasingly higher diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution remains the one advocated by sensible people on both sides, the majority of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and the ceding of territory by Israel for security reasons.
Hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will give a bit more impetus to those outside who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to put a stop to the influx of weapons into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
Non-Arab parties should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual state status at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term he failed to present his own plan for peace.
Again at the White House, he seems just as reluctant to give it his attention.
This attitude implies a deplorable view of the future.
An stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The Tobacco Plain Packaging Act comes into effect in Australia.
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases appear on packs of a dull green color, which are the same for all tobacco brands.
Australian law on tobacco and plain packaging, world-leading, comes into force, replacing brand logos and colours with a drab olive green packaging, featuring shocking images of body parts with diseases and depictions of sick children and babies due to their parents smoking.
Except for the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the cigarette packs, mandatory since Saturday, are the brand names, all printed in a small font.
This is the strictest regime in the world applied to tobacco packaging.
The Australian Federal Government states that its aim is to deter young people from smoking by removing the features that make this habit glamorous.
Trust studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before age 26, there is a 99% chance they never will.
Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek stated, citing studies which showed, for example, how girls associated a crown logo with the idea of being a princess, that it can be seen that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand.
Despite Australia having one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes not affecting multinationals' profits too much, other countries are considering taking similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would encourage the black market for tobacco, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
en: Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia said that the legislation will have serious unintended consequences.
The amount of counterfeit tobacco brought in from China and Indonesia to be sold on the streets of Australia will increase.
Others say their business has benefited since the law was passed.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, stated that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone covers to hide the unsightly images on packets had skyrocketed almost from zero two months ago when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost an appeal against the law in the Supreme Court of Australia.
Mrs. Ha stated that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesalers and was awaiting more stock.
English: "It's a good deal for us."
According to experts, the potential obstacle is the popularity of social media among the demographic targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship, and forcing most retailers to keep cigarettes out of sight, tobacco marketing has moved online.
en: Australia has banned advertising on the Internet for local businesses and websites, but it cannot restrict it on foreign websites.
EN: "If you are selling tobacco and you only have this small window to promote your products, online space is the most compelling place to be," said Becky Freeman, public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noticed an increase in reviews about brands from "ordinary citizens" posted on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook.
Is it just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video, or is some marketing company behind it all?
The British American Tobacco Australia stated that the industry is focusing more on what the new regulations involve rather than marketing.
The industry has even gone so far as to pay for Ukraine, Honduras, and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules; these countries are arguing to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, despite none of these countries having a significant trade volume with Australia.
It is likely that the WTO will issue a resolution by mid-2013.
Plibersek stated that the government had held conversations with other countries that are considering implementing similar laws regarding tobacco packaging.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the requirement to include images on cigarette packages.
Currently, they are mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey, and Ukraine.
In the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia, many smokers are defiant.
Photos don't affect me.
I simply ignore them.
Victor El Hage says, "Take the cigarette and put the pack away," as he buys a pack with a picture of a tumor in the mouth.
en: Honestly, there is only one reason I would quit smoking: for my daughter.
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack convenience store in downtown Sydney, states that uniform packs make it more difficult for him to stock the shelves.
English: "It usually took me an hour to unload a delivery; now it takes me four," says Yu.
en: "The government should have totally banned tobacco and then, that's it, it's over and we close the shop," he says while raising his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it's not so bad to be bored sometimes.
On Thanksgiving Day this year, unexpectedly I had to spend five hours in an airport because the plane we were flying on had a mechanical issue and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about being bored.
I won't lie to you.
Spending half a day in an airport waiting for a flight to arrive can be quite boring, even if you have means to stay entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, not to mention the duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and experts in child development are praising the benefits of boredom.
They believe it is okay for both us and our children to be bored sometimes.
Being bored forces the brain to look for interesting options and may foster creativity.
Since most of us are now connected to one screen or another, we don't experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom cheerfully?
Yes.
No.
But we'll talk about it later.
First of all, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" (2011, Yale University Press) states, this is not the case.
She states, "In fact, the history of boredom is very extensive."
Latin graffiti on the walls of Pompeii about boredom dating back to the 1st century AD exist.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
John D. Eastwood, a professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, states, "The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in very different ways."
After examining published research and presenting the idea to a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but not being able to, engage in an activity that fulfills you".
She states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to.
Point out that apathy does not involve the desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, it is claimed, is "the disruption of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly".
Boredom can sound awfully similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood states that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as an issue of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be within themselves.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what is actually happening to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September edition of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened to a television program at full volume in the adjacent room that had no relation, others listened to it at a low volume so it was barely audible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at all.
The group that listened to the program with the volume low showed more boredom than the other two groups; they found it difficult to concentrate, but they weren't sure why and attributed it to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or interesting task, disruption of attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
En: "On the other hand, when you are doing something boring, like detecting faulty pieces on a manufacturing line, music that distracts you can help you not to get bored."
en: In fact, we now know that moving around or doodling, actions often interpreted as signs of boredom, can actually help fight it, as it makes that person physically more alert.
English: "Research shows that children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to stay still," Professor Fenske states.
We all know what it's like to be bored at some point: a delayed flight, a monotonous speaker, an especially dull movie.
But some people have a tendency to get bored more easily than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a "boredom proneness scale" in the 1980s.
en: The scale includes questions such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that interest me that I don't have time to do it all".
Professor Stephen Vodanovich of the University of West Florida states that, using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to become bored more often than girls and specifically need more external and varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of Human and Community Development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 adolescents and their parents between seven and eight times a day via a pager.
He discovered that 32 percent of teenagers said they were bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not at school.
On the other hand, 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he didn't know if the current boredom percentages, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adolescence is a period when boredom reaches its highest levels," largely due to the fact that both children and teenagers are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, getting back to my initial question: Is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it isn't, since, taken to the extreme, it can lead us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as gambling or falling into the consumption of substances as a way to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers speak of the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for over two decades.
en: "Boredom is the brain's way of telling you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of Psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what is most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, it will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if you give your child an iPad when they are bored, it is possible they will no longer be bored, but they won't have learned to entertain themselves or to self-regulate, according to Professor Fenske.
She adds, "That ability to pace oneself applies to other situations as well."
Your child not only learns to entertain themselves, but they also learn to better regulate themselves in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant buzz of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
In our view, we need to be bored more, but boredom is too anxious and unsettling a desire to associate it with something worthwhile, they say.
People are really looking for a way to disconnect and enjoy some downtime.
In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated," she says, "it can be difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise subsides.
en: Colorado: No Instruction Manual for New Marijuana Consumption Law
es: Anthony Orozco, un estudiante de 19 años en un instituto comunitario y futbolista del sudeste de Colorado, se enfrenta a un proceso penal por poseer unas piedras de marihuana y una pipa para fumarla, algo que pronto será legal en todo el estado.
Orozco said that one September day, he and some friends were driving through Lamar, in the plains near the Kansas border, when they were stopped by the police.
en: Police found marijuana in the car and some time later Orozco received a court summons for possession of drugs and related items (minor offenses each carrying a fine of US$100) informing him of the date of the trial.
en: "They treat us like criminals," says Orozco.
And are they?
In the weeks of uncertainty following the vote in Colorado to legalize possession of small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the response in hundreds of minor drug possession cases depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of minor marijuana possession offenses are being dismissed both here and in the state of Washington, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped filing charges against those over 21 for small-scale possession, which will be legally approved once the law comes into effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in more conservative districts of Colorado have committed to moving forward with open cases for marijuana possession and are still citing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains, are voting to prevent newly authorized marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
en: "Everything is changing so quickly, I don't know what's next," said Daniel J. Oates, Chief of Police in Aurora, just east of Denver.
Those responsible for regulations in the state of Washington are also looking into the matter.
They are still seeking advice to set up a system of production, manufacturing, distribution and sales licenses; all before the deadline of December 1st, 2013.
They say that, for better or for worse, Colorado is ahead of most states when it comes to regulating the use of marijuana, first for therapeutic purposes and now for recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide," says Brian E. Smith, spokesperson for the Washington State Liquor and Cannabis Board.
Mr. Smith admits, however, that any place or system can only make suggestions as to what might work.
"There is no true precedent to serve as a model," he states.
Washington's law, known as I-502, will go into effect on December 6th, leaving a year in which things will be in a grey area as the licensing system in the state will not yet exist, but possession will be legal.
Additionally, there are some delicate mechanical issues that must be resolved during that period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state's requirement to provide "adequate access" to authorized marijuana and its prohibition of conducting cannabis businesses within a 300-meter radius of schools, parks, playgrounds, or childcare centers.
It will be most difficult to locate an authorized cannabis business in urban areas, particularly in the Seattle metropolitan area, according to Ben Livingston, spokesperson for the newly formed Legal Cannabis Center research group.
On November 21, Oates, the Chief of Police in Aurora, sent an email to his police officers informing them that the City Attorney would no longer be filing legal actions for minor marijuana possession offenses for individuals over 21 years of age and that police would no longer be filing charges for such offenses "with immediate effect".
Chief of Police Oates stated that they would be responsible for enforcing the city ordinance regulating the cultivation of marijuana for therapeutic purposes and that they would continue to pursue drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County, in Northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck represents a more conservative view.
After the vote, he assured that his office would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, primarily to pressure consumers into seeking treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
Our office has the obligation to take legal action against offenses that were criminal at the time they were committed, Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The answer has been complicated even in places like Mesa County's rural county, where voters rejected the initiative to legalize marijuana.
The police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer cite adults for possession of small amounts.
Pete Hautzinger, District Attorney of the county, supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending possession cases.
"I don't consider I'm wasting my time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he stated.
Despite 55 percent of voters supporting the measure, it was never considered that bringing recreational marijuana consumption into the government and judicial system would be easy.
The conflicting reactions arising throughout the state reveal a marked ambivalence among officials regarding the state's grand ecological experiment.
en: Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer representing defendants charged with marijuana possession and a local spokesperson for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws, states, "It's a cultural barrier with the district attorneys."
He has been taking people to court for so long that they still can't accept that it's legal, he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana the same as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are preparing to become the test cases nationally for drug legalization.
Lawyers and state officials, while having a new legal sales frontier, are also eagerly awaiting guidance from the federal government, which still views the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Supporters of marijuana legalization are hoping that the Department of Justice will relent.
Despite some notable arrests of patients and sellers of marijuana for therapeutic purposes, the federal government has largely allowed businesses selling marijuana for these purposes to exist in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Although it is likely that drug enforcement agents will not kick down doors to confiscate a small bag of drugs, they are likely to be reluctant to allow the operation of state-regulated stores for the sale of marijuana for recreational use, allowed under the new law," said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy advisor to the Obama administration.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before Election Day, some local governments approved moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, despite it being around a year before any of them can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose adopted a six-month ban and is likely to approve it next week.
We don't want to put ourselves in a situation where we authorize someone and then have a major problem at the federal level, explained Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We are studying in favor of what the community voted for as opposed to voting in favor of what the state voted for.
Many questions arise in this regard.
English: Petronella Wyatt: "I was harassed out of Oxford for being a Tory"
Students are not attacked for their views alone anymore.
I cannot remember a single moment in my life when I have not been dreaming of getting a place at the University of Oxford.
Both my father and my older brother had been to what I thought was the best place in the world to learn, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, two weeks after taking up my place at Worcester College in the late 80s to study History, I had already packed my bags, which set off the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started to cry.
My friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard newspaper reported that I had left because I could not tolerate some university peers having sexual relations in the room next door.
A.N. Wilson jokingly announced that he was leaving because he was being forced to drink out of chipped cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Despite my extravagant name, nor the fact that I came from a private school.
I was bullied for one reason only, which in the cradle of supposed enlightenment was something intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative Party.
Maybe you are wondering what this has to do with anything now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of right-wing students is facing similar persecution.
Institutionalized and growing hatred towards Conservative party students at Oxford is so great that, last week, a group of them demanded the same level of equal rights as those given to homosexuals, the disabled, and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the JCR (graduate student body) at Corpus Christi College claim they are "often seriously sidelined, personally attacked and treated as unwelcome persons" due to their political views.
They want to create a position on their college's Equal Opportunity Committee to ensure they can express their opinions freely.
Their situation was not helped by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" which portrayed Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazis in its coverage of student politics.
en: Joe Cooke, a postgraduate student and former President of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), was shown in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a silver-handled cane.
In other universities, conservative students say they are being treated like "scapegoats" for the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20 years old and Vice President of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Nottingham, stated in a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People assume we are like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing us.
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who proposed the motion for greater protection, states that the atmosphere is "uncomfortable", while Stephanie Cherill, 19-year-old and incoming president of the OUCA, claims that the attitude of JCR members towards those who are centre-right has worsened.
"This poses a threat to the intellectual debate environment, as well as to the well-being of members," he states.
During my first few weeks in Oxford I was lonelier than ever.
I entered university in September 1986, I was an 18-year-old terribly shy young woman.
The hatred towards the Conservative Party was at its highest.
Last year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an honorary degree in light of the cuts to Higher Education funding.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder in terror.
During the first few days of the welcome week for new university students, when the new students were getting to know each other and their professors, I got a taste of the bitterness that was to come.
I discovered that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery made of conservative university students, but they also participated in it willingly.
The miners' strike policy, privatization, and the government's opposition to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa reached the wooden halls of the seminar.
At the first one I attended, I had to translate French texts from the 18th century and I was not prepared for what came next.
Ms. Wyatt, said the late Professor Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
en: I didn't say a word.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake batter, knew how to vent his bad temper well.
"Are Thatcherites refusing to learn French or are they just stupid?", he asked.
The other university students laughed.
My eyes were burning from the tears I was trying to hold back.
en: "I suggest you take French classes in your free time, as long as you're not too busy getting to know people," growled Pitt.
I returned to my room like a soul in distress.
That night I sat alone for dinner at the university; then I felt a light pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who presented himself as a member of the OUCA.
en: "I know who you are," he said kindly.
en: I'm afraid that's how it goes.
They pick on anyone suspected of being a Tory.
It's very complicated for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be even worse for you.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be Labourists.
Later, at a local pub, I tried to cowardly disguise myself.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Mrs. Thatcher said.
That trick turned out to be useless.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contaminated.
Other students adopted that little song.
I became the dirty pervert.
One asked, "How do Tories have sex?"
en: They are beating each other up, right?
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be obligated to hang out with people who think like me only after dark?
Should I become a laborer and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years ahead of me seemed like a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory lecturer was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my university college.
They hated him for not only being a Conservative party member but also an advisor to Thatcher on foreign policy and one of the people who wrote her speeches.
I was just there.
I hated the place because I considered it provincial and insignificant and for its adherence to the Marxist-determinist vision of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
en: "You won't be happy here," he told me.
I started commuting daily from Oxford to my parents' home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he was studying there in the 1940s, all political viewpoints were accepted.
"But if it's the best place in the world," he said sadly.
They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had impeccable attitudes.
Her aching eyes began to cloud over.
Give them another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke around.
en: It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional resilience was deteriorating.
My friend, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to the pressure and had renounced his creed.
Next week, during a seminar where another professor of History had insinuated, speaking completely seriously, that I was an "enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
I was red with embarrassment inside, admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me and called them "stupid old people".
The truce lasted for a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my university career at Oxford.
At that time, my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch's press.
My door was locked.
I was cowering inside in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my bags and caught the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you will call me a weak crybaby.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it is Oxford, which has not only educated 14 Conservative Prime Ministers but which, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety.
To mark the opening of the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Couture" this week in London, ABC speaks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer.
en: Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
en: The designer was acknowledged at the opening of "Valentino: Maestro de la Costura", an awe-inspiring retrospective that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his "maison" over the last 50 years.
She says with her unmistakable Italian accent, "I love this palace."
This show is the finale of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rare and distant world of nobility.
In the first room of this exhibition, open until next March 3rd, there are plenty of private letters and photos with the signature of the most prominent of the aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, passing through Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margarita of England.
Valentino displays those personal memories as trophies of his social ascent: from humble dressmaker in the city of Voghera, in northern Italy, to international "jet-set" idol.
Being in love with royalty is nothing wrong.
en: "At least they don't put out their cigarette butts on your magnificent carpet like some beautiful pop music celebrities do," says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular host and entertains with generosity and elegance.
Everyone loved being invited to his chalet in Gstaad," says Heini Thyssen's ex-wife, an intimate of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to notoriety.
And yet, it is a star.
Valeria Mazza wearing a Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza also does not forget the charisma of the fashion designer.
Many years ago, after a parade in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went to have dinner at his apartment.
We were twenty people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of the floor, the decoration, the food, the music, his spirit was seen and felt everywhere.
en: "He made each of the guests feel important and loved," remembers the "top model," who began working with him during Paris Fashion Week in 1995.
en: "It never goes out of style because its designs are works of art," she finishes.
Nobility Parade
Life for Garavani is not a story of obsessions, but of well-reciprocated loves.
He loves people with good manners and better credentials, and they love him in return.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glamorous sixty-meter-long catwalk that proposes a role reversal: the visitor takes the place of the models and must strut down the catwalk to behold a dream "audience" adorned with masterpieces from Valentino, such as the dress Jackie Kennedy chose for her wedding with Aristotle Onassis, the wardrobe used by Monica Vitti in "La Notte", or a wool and fur coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
In that mannequin crowd, names such as Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria, and Sofía of Habsburg shine.
Naty Abascal and the fashion designer in 2006.
Many of those customers say that the first Valentino is like the first love, "impossible to forget".
I remember it perfectly.
It was a pair of trousers, a shirt, a "Gillette" vest and a jacket from the Fall-Winter 1971-1972 collection.
Naty Abascal, one of the designer's muses, says, "It was a gift he made for me."
I prefer him above all others for his femininity, his great love for women, because he enhances our beauty," adds the former Duchess of Feria.
I really like the colors you use, they have great light and are "donors" to the face.
The proportions are perfect.
The fashion icon and trendsetter Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg cannot forget the first time she wore a Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed of being old enough and having the opportunity to wear one of their evening gowns...
Finally, the time came at the end of the 90s.
I bought my first Valentino dress to wear to a party at my cousin Prince Edward of Ligne's castle.
It was a red dress, with ruffled skirt, draped "corsage" and off-the-shoulder neckline.
en: "It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
en: Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his obsession is the timeless, explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
The Princess of Arenberg carefully guards her evening gowns from the fashion designer because "a dress is not just a dress, it's also a set of memories it carries."
The "king" of fashion
The grand finale of the Somerset House exhibition is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her marriage to Pavlos of Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "ragazze" (as the dressmaker calls his seamstresses) to make that ivory silk dress with pearl inlays, twelve different types of lace and a four and a half meter long train.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the highest authority in the specialized press, that dress represents a milestone of haute couture from the late 20th century, "the return of the high society customers".
For years clouded by the "savoir-être" of the elite, Valentino is now its best exemplar.
en: Knight of the Grand Cross (the highest distinction in Italy), Knight of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters, decorated with the Legion of Honor, Garavani accumulates as many honors as any of the husbands of his clients.
en: "I have always been drawn to your refinement, your calmness, your neat and perfect look," D'Arenberg acknowledges.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Orsay Museum.
He was at the table of Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, a great friend of mine.
He was impeccable, time stands still for him.
If a princess says so...
The hardest job in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilos of sulfur across steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their job is a living hell and others who literally work in hell.
en: Anto Wijaya is one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to descend every day to the bottom of his crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After breaking off large chunks of sulfur, which together weigh about 70 kilograms, he carries them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It's only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters in altitude, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb at a snail's pace, keeping their balance and measuring their steps carefully to avoid slipping and falling off the cliff.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
en: The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents per euro for every kilo of sulfur they extract.
Once they reach the top, they make their way through the tourists taking pictures of them as if they were circus monkeys and, carrying their heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters above sea level.
This is about PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano and, literally, its workers since 1960, paying them 662 Indonesian rupiah (5 cents of euro) per kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents Euro) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
As Anto, who usually makes three trips a day, explains, "Normally we carry 70 kilos, so we make 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip."
It takes three hours for each one and he ends up exhausted, but he is able to make 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems like a pittance for such inhumane effort, it is three times what one would earn in the field.
The miners' wage is very high here, where coffee harvesting is paid at 15,000 rupias (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupias (167 euros), explains the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
en: There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the job wasn't too hard, but Anto has returned to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a weighty reason that, in Indonesia, is as powerful as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindu, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27 years old, Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen for three years, and the sulfur has already started to take its toll on him despite wearing a mask and special glasses.
She has asthma, is breathing with difficulty, is constantly coughing, and her eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
It is the price you must pay to get your dream.
She promises in very good English that she will work two more years in order to open a store or study Spanish or French.
Punished by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden hut with other porters, he rises every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
Anto braves the shadows, descending into the crater with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
Approximately 400 porters carry the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its hefty profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs nor supplies any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and at their own weight.
In fact, they don't even see the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) camera fee that, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee, the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school, protests, "This work is for beasts, not for people."
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will endure working "as much as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps miners in the thick columns coming out of the volcano, they are so tough that none of them complain about suffering from serious illnesses... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and sores on the shoulders, which have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
en: Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilograms at his 53 years old.
He and his colleagues start harvesting 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano every day, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away on a goat path through the undergrowth.
"I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life," proclaims Unainik, opening his mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the oldest, who is 30 years old, also works loading sulfur.
Time passes, but the misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest jobs in the world: the one done by the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy.
Singaporeans blame the rat race, stress, and the cost of property and education for not having children.
en: Singapore's population needs to grow.
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let's fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem unbelievable that these verses are part of a mint pill advertisement, but despite that - or perhaps because of that - the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
Let's put a bao (bun) in the oven, a reference to Singapore's low birth rate, as part of a rap song.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, hopes that the advertisement will draw attention to the problem in a humorous way.
en: Creative Director Douglas Hamilton says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill their "national duty".
This is something purely online, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves, so we felt this was an issue we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as launching perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating events.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why not be as creative as possible in solving this problem, which is to compose a rap?
Two children
The Singapore government takes it more seriously.
Spend US$1,300 per year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leaders and strict social controls.
The fertility rate of Singapore, according to its National Population Division, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 -known as the replacement rate- was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
en: Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policies of the National Population Division, states that this is due to "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
en: This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family,” he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in singleness, and a delay in marriage and childbirth, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aiming to drastically increase immigration to address the population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where thinly-veiled xenophobia against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, abounds, criticizing them for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party experienced its worst electoral result since independence last year.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to address the issue, with higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in birth rate has known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenue, healthcare costs, and immigration policies, the example of Singapore is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to prevent the construction of too many small houses.
For example, it has started to affect the real estate sector.
The Urban Development Authority has taken control of the number of small apartments, known as "shoeboxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have 46 square meters of surface area and have been very successful in sales.
en However, there is concern that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family-oriented homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, Managing Director of EL Developers property firm, says his "shoebox" units sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular in the sense that units sell out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new regulations provide clearer guidance for developers, who were previously hindered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, speaking to Singaporeans working in the Central Financial District, it seems they will not have much effect.
People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off, says a young executive.
Others may have children.
"But for me it's important to have my own money and time," says another young person in their twenties.
Men and women cite their career, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons preventing them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the final say.
Private offline is private online.
Privacy.
En: According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is the quality of being private or "the scope of private life that one has the right to protect from any intrusion".
en: What is private for a minor under 16 years old?
How does this definition apply to your everyday life and social media?
Do you understand the dangers you are exposed to by airing online situations that you would probably not share offline?
The newspaper interviewed five boys between the ages of ten and fifteen, frequent users of the internet.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with "something very personal" on a personal level, and "in the username and name" when applied to social networks.
Jorge, aged ten, says, "I wouldn't post my deepest secrets," when trying to explain the meaning of private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
en: "They are very secret secrets, my mom can know them, but not everyone," she says.
I post beautiful pictures or game related content on Facebook.
I also have fun with my acquaintances.
She says, "I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine, or of someone making a fool of themselves."
The child recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene photographs, of naked people, of crimes or to write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on Facebook and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother is included, she has the key to one of the accounts.
I opened Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
en: "I don't know if they will answer me, I'm just posting them," he adds.
en: "Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends quickly," he says.
I have no doubt in answering that I would never accept a request from a stranger.
I wouldn't take advice from someone recommending a stranger.
en: Jose's case, at 14 years old, is different.
The teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter he admits not knowing 20 of the people added to his friends list.
en: "I'm not scared, because we have something in common, like music for example," he says.
According to the boy, no one has hinted at him or asked for his home address or phone number.
en: "If they pressured me or demanded it, I would simply take them out of my account," he admits.
José became a follower of Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unfamiliar with the experiences of what is now known as cyberbullying.
My friend's acquaintance was being extorted on a social media platform.
They threatened him and demanded money.
She claims she never knew who she was.
en: According to Jose, the victim did not close the account.
He only made it private.
Then explain a series of steps for setting up the account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this guy would post pictures of acquaintances in embarrassing or awkward situations.
Yes, I would do it, whether I dislike them or have a grudge against them.
en: "Although I know that is cyberbullying," she states.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and holder of a degree in Education and Learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents it is important to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
en: The internet emerged as a means to search for information, but with the emergence of these sites the rules of the game changed, he mentions.
Porras states that academic Marc Prensky, a Master of Education from Yale University and author of the work Digital Natives and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Native digital natives are those children and young adults who were born with technology.
We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them, even though we are still learning ourselves,” he says.
Commenting that the topic is complex, "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion about what is appropriate or not to spread, publish or say at an age where maturity does not allow for it".
Be selective when what matters most to you is being popular and having thousands of friends without thinking of the consequences, adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and teenagers about privacy is through questions that make them reflect.
en: "Telling them not to do it doesn't help," adds.
Below, Porras lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the internet?
Would you like them to post a picture of you like the one you posted of a friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission to tag them when you label photos from parties?
English: And one more, does everyone need to know what you're doing every moment?
Another point is to make them realize that they should act online the same way they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"One should act with respect, morality, and other principles both on and off the internet," they affirm.
Surveillance
En: Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher, and educational consultant, states that it is essential for parents to read the social media policies carefully.
By understanding each clause they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the implications of opening an Internet account.
For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or posted," he says.
According to Guardia, it is key to remind children of the lesson of "don't talk to strangers".
The Unasur Summit ended without making the Lima Declaration public.
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending presidents, being made public.
en:  Efe tried multiple times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially said that it would be delivered after the closing, but then they stated that it would be published at some point on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during a brief press conference.
The access of journalists to the information of the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was provided by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discontent of hundreds of journalists from different national and international media outlets who were asking for more data.
Later, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it is the statement of Humala, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being repeatedly requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that had previously been announced was not released either.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international conferences, Peruvian authorities strived to ensure secure transmission systems for all journalists but limited the acquisition of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling from the Hague Court to settle a border dispute between the two countries.
en: Peruvian President Ollanta Humala and Chilean President Sebastián Piñera met during the regional meeting and reaffirmed their commitment to respect the decision of the International Court of Justice (ICJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both sides in the process that Lima has presented against Santiago.
"We will abide by and execute the ruling that defines the differences we are bringing to this international court today," said Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
en: Chile has been, is, and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties, and international courts," added Piñera, and shook hands with Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
Both presidents' confirmation that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of the international court, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it deemed seriously wrong.
The summit took place with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 following the ousting of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The leader read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and action lines were set for 31 projects among South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
English: Among the agreements adopted, it was mentioned that the countries of UNASUR will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence".
He reported that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to the internet at a low price in all corners of South America, and to address jointly and efficiently the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "Latin American economic consolidation should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and glimpse a better future for our peoples," added Humala.
We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of spaces in South America, especially in rural and border areas...connecting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian president in a read message.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located on the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
en: Furthermore, the final document mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
We hope that the electoral process in that country serves for its reincorporation to the Union of South American Nations, from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and of good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to discuss respectfully the maritime dispute following a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogota.
en: Santos said, "It is possible that I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)."
"Let's review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua," he emphasized.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are set to meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they are expected to attend the inauguration of the new president of the country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Likewise, as part of the summit, the Defense Ministers of the bloc met previously to approve the Action Plan of the year 2013, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on Defense in the region.
en: Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of UNASUR, although the last country is suspended.
en: Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
en: "South America must learn from Europe to integrate a citizenship": Rafael Correa
English: Ecuadorian President Rafael Correa stated today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case, must learn from Europe".
Correa, who participated in the 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR), held in Lima, declared to the state-run TV Peru that the Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and in other conflicts, "but now they are practically one nation".
He defended the project of establishing South American citizenship that is encouraged by the member countries of Unasur.
en: "We must achieve the free mobility of citizens and workers throughout any South American country, as is already the case with members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to take us back to the past," he warned.
The Ecuadorian President also expressed his support for the reconstitution of the Organization of American States (OAS) under the premise of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those who have signed the San José Pact on Human Rights.
Those who lecture never commit to anything, whereas we South Americans sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under the funding of the United States," he said in reference to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
en: Correa asserted that he is not regretful of that decision because he has not betrayed his principles, but rather has respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He added that, at the time, "there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and his process would not be respected."
He also criticized the Swedish justice system for requiring him to submit to questioning in its territory for an alleged sexual offense when "Swedish legislation itself allows it to be done via video conference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa stated that there is a risk of Assange's physical and mental health deteriorating.
The Ecuadorian president said, "I haven't spoken to him since he's been at our embassy, but the ambassador told me he had a minor lung problem, nothing serious."
There is a danger of physical and mental health deteriorating due to being confined in a small space without being able to do outdoor exercise.
en: "That complicates the health of anyone," he added.
Correa stated that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, through the granting of a safe-conduct that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European legal authorities and he stressed that there have been conversations with London in search of a solution to the confinement of the founder of WikiLeaks.
We do not negotiate on human rights, we do not use that term in this case, but there have been ongoing conversations.
The solution to this problem lies in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden, and European legal authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is taking a series of proceedings in different European courts, mentioned.
He said that "if Britain grants the safe-conduct tomorrow, this will be over."
If Sweden, as its legislation allows and as it has done in other cases, interrogates Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London or interrogates him via Skype tomorrow, this problem will be solved.
en: Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of freedom of the press and clarified that what he does not tolerate is "mediocrity, bad faith and lies, which distort freedom of expression".
en: "The greatest enemies of press freedom are not evil and corrupt politicians, but bad journalists driven by profit, blackmail, and extortion," he said.
In that regard, he congratulated that it is no longer "neither bankers nor hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador", and he anticipated that if reelected he will "deepen the revolution to continue on the right path and direction".
President Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay in Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the organization "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coup-mongering disguised as legality" because in reality it "destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian President also considered "perfectly pertinent" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate now the maritime boundaries between both countries after the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which benefited Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty.
For the moment, that ruling is not being followed.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but must be overcome by the will to walk together.
We must process them broadly in order to overcome them and move forward.
He also trusted in a good conclusion of the maritime boundaries dispute between Peru and Chile that is being held in the same court, and he opined that "it is right for Latin America to look for international instances if the two countries commit to accept the ruling, however hard it may be".
In reference to the possibility of running as a candidate in the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador to seek a third consecutive term, he stated that he sees this possibility "with a lot of optimism and joy, although sometimes it can be quite tough".
Correa stated that if he loses the February 2013 elections, he will retire from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as that of Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected through political power.
"My political movement believed that it was I who guaranteed that probable victory, so we have to accept that responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last term in office and then we would step out of public life.
We lose either way.
He said, "It's a decision."
Correa also referred to the new health treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro and he told me that he traveled for a treatment that was already planned, routine, and that he waited for the campaign to be over before returning to Cuba.
"It does not mean a relapse in President Chavez's health condition," he commented.
The Ecuadorian Head of State participated today in Lima in the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to sustain progress, equality, and security.
Deaths from AIDS today are caused by late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed positive for HIV.
"It was like a bomb dropped on me," she recalls of the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make "a little softer," to no avail.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take charge of his illness and started to research it; with such determination that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the longest-serving patients of the HIV Unit at the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), which he arrived at in 1994 after several battles.
En: Fabrizio has been living with Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine at the beginning of the 90s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options, and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
Then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, many people still come when the virus has already wreaked havoc, "exhausted" their immune system and become victims of opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least from the first reported cases, "the great achievement at this moment means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HCG HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after referring to this information being endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
HIV/AIDS specialist and infectologist Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a death sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment to the immune system that patients present at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a CD4 count of 200 and 50 years when they report 500 CD4.
In plain words, the above means that someone who is diagnosed with HIV positive at 25 years old, under these terms "as long as they stay in control they can live without problems until 75 years old", the interviewee explained.
en: To put this progress into perspective, it is worth noting that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality rates have significantly decreased in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (annual report from UNAIDS), it is also true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In 2011, only 255 people died in Jalisco, and there have been 187 deaths up to May of this year; nevertheless, it is assured that there is universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
en: Why are there still deaths?
en: It seems to me that the problem is not access to treatment.
I envision it this way, this is what has happened in our hospital.
For the past 12 years, we have not had a shortage of medication. The problem is that patients arrive very advanced because they are unaware of their infection status, that is, in late stages of the disease.
He gave a striking statistic: "Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have some opportunistic infection. What needs to be done to have a greater impact on global mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, therefore, offer screening tests on a massive scale to all those who need it."
Experts and officials from the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) agree with Fabrizio, a patient who went to a private laboratory to get tested for HIV only because a friend had done it. Despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and had even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor which is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don't want to know anything.
en: "If I'm going to die anyway, I might as well party three times a week," they say, not in my case.
The change was for the better, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To date, their parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like anyone else.
Fabrizio listed, "I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of myself and the other person," as he accepted to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate those who, on the occasion of World AIDS Day, are afraid.
Get tested if you have been at risk, the sooner you know if you are HIV positive the better, and if you already have a diagnosis, learn that you can live like anyone else, being responsible.
That, your message, summarizes the battle cry for AIDS this 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
Great are the gaps between health programs and the common citizen, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the cause around HIV.
And the biggest one is in prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "there has indeed been an increase in the distribution of condoms; before we were given one or two, now we get packages of a hundred, and that's great, but there are still people who don't have access to a condom today," he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you want them?" is a common question, with sarcasm and value judgments from social workers, school counselors, pharmacists, and health care professionals, which teenagers do not want to be exposed to, the communicator assured.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms should not only be behind the counters and those hundred should be in dispensers in public bathrooms of the places frequented by young people.
en: It is not encouraging promiscuity.
It's not about paying for the beers and the motel, as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if there would be distribution of condoms in his Administration.
en: "That's not how sexuality works, it's best to make condoms available to those who are already engaging in sexual activity," she noted.
