A United States appeals court upholding a ruling that disregards the debt restructuring of the Vitro Group achieved through a Mexican bankruptcy proceeding sets a troubling precedent for any Mexican company with operations in the neighboring country that has solvency issues.
It would thus appear that the survival procedures of firms allowed by Mexican laws are not valid in the country of the stripes and stars, contrary to international agreements.
In practical terms, the endorsement of the ruling issued on June 15th by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless against the possibility of having their properties seized across the Rio Grande.
However, the resolution opens the door for the main glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court, alleging three inconsistencies.
At the outset, while the judge in the case states that creditors must abide by the United States Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans says that the primary procedure is the Mexican bankruptcy proceeding.
The first point would involve disregarding international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of transnational companies.
English: In fact, the United Nations Model Law on International Commercial Arbitration was created for that purpose, with the American Law Institute as the arbiter.
Second, the ruling states that without intercompany voting, recognized in the critical mass of the bankruptcy proceedings, the debts owed to its parent company by Vitro's subsidiaries would not have achieved the required majority to approve the restructuring.
However, Mexican laws recognize the possibility.
In fact, Vitro's has not been the first case to accept the scheme.
Here are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcies.
The truth is, even after subtracting the votes of the subsidiaries, the creditors of Vitro who fought against it in the US Courts, i.e. the "vulture funds" such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergence, Elliot International and Liverpool Limited, will not have achieved a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
The Appeals Court omits the data.
From another angle, this blames Vitro for the difficult situation it faced from 2008 onwards, sidestepping the serious economic crisis that the United States faced, with its repercussions felt throughout the country.
The Gonzalez Sada family firm will file a motion for reconsideration with the appeals court itself, so that the vote can reach the full court, that is, the five magistrates, since only three voted.
If this does not succeed, the recourse of certiorari will be sought, which requires the review of the process by a higher authority, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
The seriousness of the case is that the court disregarded a document sent by the Mexican government under the figure of amicus curiae ("friend of the court"), in which the procedure followed by Vitro under the framework of the Commercial Bankruptcy Law is detailed, indicating that it was carried out in accordance with the agreements signed by both countries to match it with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Law.
Furthermore, it is noted that the country adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law, i.e. the rules set for cross-border insolvency cases, which guarantee equity for debtors and creditors.
Two-way carom shot: they hit Vitro and they hit the country.
