Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball has been my life."
Basketball globetrotter Hector "Hetin" Reyes was connected to the sport of basketball for over 60 years and, thanks to him, traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as extensive a mental recollection of the local basketball history as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before suffering a stroke that confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes had been immersed in sports for over 60 years, whether as a minor league player, a player in the National Superior Basketball League, an agent and manager in the BSN with the Bayamón Cowboys, or president of the Basketball Federation.
Throughout my life, I have worn many hats in basketball, including multiple at once, such as when I was President of the BSN, General Manager of the National Team, and Federal President during the 90s," Reyes recalled during a visit from Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
en: Basketball has been my life.
King is not exaggerating in making that assertion.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia that denote his extensive career, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all the memories he cherishes most, those that recall his time with the Cowboys from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he completed 15 years as co-owner or owner of the franchise, are the most emotionally charged.
Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight championships of the Cowboys from 1967, either as a representative, co-representative or leader.
It was many years of satisfaction, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
Then I said goodbye in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy debuted in the BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz took charge, who was a great manager," Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had coached here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me, "I have a really strong player for you, 6'7" tall.
Do you want it?
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
en: Bartow then recommended sniper Raymond Gausse, who was native-born and one of our best shots.
I remember he said that if Mincy had given a championship to Bayamon, Gausse would help bring another one.
The Cowboys' championship with Gausse was enjoyed, but from a distance, as by 1988 he was already a federal manager.
For that time I preferred to enjoy their performances and Mincy's on the National Team.
I remember when we won against the United States for the first time during the Pre-Olympic in Mexico in 1989.
en: Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth place and should have been bronze if it weren't for that Canadian referee who made us repeat the final play twice, said Reyes.
Is that World Cup 1990 team the best National Team you've ever seen?
He is among the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and gave the US team a run for their money, which was pretty similar to the one that won us the bronze at the World Cup.
That team not only repeated Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also had (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter young, the Leon brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to be in 90 due to a knee injury.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but gave us a gold medal and great joy was the 1995 Pre-Olympic in Neuquén, Argentina.
With role players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea, and a junior Rolando Hourruitiner in substitution of the players suspended for the Panamerican fiasco in Mar del Plata, we won gold against all odds.
What has been the best player from Puerto Rico?
No doubt, that was Piculín Ortiz.
His international tournament stats are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at that level like Piculín did.
And that's not even counting his track record in the various leagues he played in.
Who has been the best Puerto Rican leader?
That is very difficult.
We have had a very good litter that includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
